<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Developer faces writ for Pounds 16m transfer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Broome, the property developer behind Battersea Leisure, the scheme
that failed to redevelop the Battersea Power Station, is the subject of a
High Court writ concerning an unexplained cash transfer.
The writ, which was issued by the liquidator of Battersea Leisure on May 27,
concerns the transfer six years ago of Pounds 16m from Battersea Leisure to
Alton Towers, the Staffordshire theme park formerly run by Mr Broome.
Mr Alan Lewis of Arthur Andersen, accountants, liquidator of Battersea
Leisure, is seeking the return of the money. The protective writ was issued
just before the six-year time limit for bringing legal action ran out.
The proceedings were described as 'preposterous' by a spokesman for the
Broome Group. 'The Broome Group strenuously denies that the directors have
executed their responsibilities in any way other than with total correctness
concerning all financial arrangements in the group,' the spokesman said.
He added: 'It is understood that Arthur Andersen had not contacted the
company's accountants Touche Ross, due to time constraints, in order to
acquaint themselves with the relevant facts prior to issuing a protective
writ - which has not been served.'
Mr Broome's plans to redevelop Battersea Power station started in 1987 when
his company Battersea Group, formerly Alton Towers, acquired 85 per cent of
the Battersea site for Pounds 18m. But plans to turn it into a leisure
complex were halted in 1990, after the scheme ran out of funds. Battersea
Leisure eventually went into liquidation. Control of the site passed to
Parkview, a company owned by the Hwang Brothers of Hong Kong, which intends
to develop a hotel, office complex and leisure scheme.
In 1987, at the same time as Mr Broome's company bought its 85 per cent
stake of the Battersea site, Mr Broome bought 15 per cent of the site for
his own account. He then sold this minority stake at a sharply increased
price of Pounds 16.5m in 1988 to Alton Towers. Mr Broome was paid Pounds 11m
of the proceeds in the form of shares in Alton Towers, while he received the
remaining Pounds 5.5m in cash.
Mr Broome sold Alton Towers, the Staffordshire theme park, to Pearson, the
group that publishes the Financial Times, for Pounds 60m in March 1990.
The writ has been issued against ATB (Staffs) Ltd which is Mr Broome's
company, Mr Broome, his wife and two other directors of ATB (Staff) Ltd.
</TEXT>
