<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Cages 'cause extreme suffering' to battery hens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Battery cages cause extreme suffering to egg-laying hens, a government
adviser on animal health has found after a wide-ranging review of scientific
evidence.
Mr Mike Baxter, director of Brunel University's Design Centre, concluded
that hens suffer in a number of ways by not being able to perform natural
functions in very small cages. His report, published today, is likely to add
to pressure on the government to restrict battery farming.
Groups such as the animal welfare society the RSPCA have long campaigned for
battery farming to be banned. About 85 per cent - or 40m - of Britain's
egg-laying hens are kept in battery cages. Last month the Commons
agriculture committee in a report on the poultry industry concluded that a
ban on battery cages would not be a realistic propo-sition.
The committee said: 'Non-cage systems have their own welfare drawbacks and
any wholesale switch to alternative systems would not necessarily enhance
the overall welfare of laying hens.'
The government says it is pushing Brussels to review European Union rules on
battery hens. New regulations come into force in January, increasing the
amount of space each hen must have from 450 sq cm to 600 sq cm.
The egg industry has said that the costs of any further changes in the
regulations would be too great a burden.
Mr Baxter, who sits on the government's Farm Animal Welfare Council, says in
his report in The Veterinary Record that hens are unable to perform natural
nesting functions in a wire mesh cage. There is nowhere for them to perch,
they cannot indulge in dust-bathing or foraging and their bones are weakened
by lack of movement.
The Farm Animal Welfare Council was set up by the government in 1979 as an
independent body to advise on legislation. The council has not yet made any
official recommendations on battery hens.
</TEXT>
