<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Both sides upbeat in BBC dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Both sides in the industrial dispute at the BBC yesterday appeared
optimistic that talks today at Acas, the conciliation service, could lead to
a settlement of the action which has already halted programmes for two
24-hour periods, Diane Summers writes.
Bectu, the main technical union, and the NUJ journalists' union called off
action planned for yesterday and dropped plans for a stoppage tomorrow.
The dispute is about the implementation of performance pay and the
decentralisation to individual BBC directorates of negotiations on some
terms of employment.
BBC management said it hoped that once certain reassurances and
clarifications had been given at Acas the unions would 'feel free to put the
matter to a ballot of their members with a recommendation to accept' the
package. The corporation emphasised that it was 'not in a position to move
any further' on the substance of the offer.
</TEXT>
