<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Building material deficit declines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's trade deficit in building materials fell 16.7 per cent last year
to Pounds 1.44bn - the lowest since 1986.
The improvement was led by a 15 per cent rise in the value of exports, which
increased from Pounds 2.3bn to Pounds 2.6bn, figures published by the
Department of the Environment show.
There is concern, however, that the deficit might rise again when material
bottlenecks start to emerge as the construction industry recovers. The
prices of a number of British-produced materials and components have risen
sharply this year.
Sales abroad by British companies have been boosted by the 1992 devaluation
of sterling and by large productivity gains.
Last year's improvement in exports is encouraging because continental
Europe, the main overseas market for British building materials, was itself
in deep recession.
British steel suppliers and fabricators have been particularly successful in
breaking into Continental markets. The trade surplus in structural steel,
for example, rose last year from Pounds 65.3m to Pounds 179.9m.
The surplus in steel reinforcing bars for concrete doubled from Pounds 39.3m
to Pounds 80.9m, while the surplus on steel tubes and pipes increased 46 per
cent to Pounds 65.78m.
British manufacturers of other building products also saw substantial gains
last year, with the trade surplus on wallpaper rising 43 per cent to Pounds
141.9m.
Imports of building materials rose only 1.5 per cent to Pounds 4.1bn. Of
this, more than Pounds 1bn was due to the importation of raw and
semi-finished timber. Much of this is hardwood which Britain is unable to
produce.
Ministers have repeatedly criticised the construction industry for the high
level of imports, which peaked at Pounds 4.7bn in 1989, causing a record
deficit of Pounds 2.8bn. There will be continuing concern about the high
level of imports of some manufactured products, even though the overall
total has reduced substantially.
Decorative glazed ceramic tiles, for example, incurred a trade deficit of
Pounds 79.6m last year, although this was less than the previous year's
Pounds 102.5m. Builders' ironmongery, such as doorknobs and other small
items, had a trade deficit of Pounds 195.3m last year, only slightly down on
the previous year's Pounds 197.87m.
</TEXT>
