<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / PM deals blow to Post Office sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prime minister has ordered Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, to redraft plans for privatisation of the Post Office. The move
is another setback for politicians and industrialists who want to see the
organisation sold.
Whitehall officials say Mr John Major has rejected an early draft of a green
paper by the Department of Trade and Industry on the privatisation of Royal
Mail and Parcelforce, the parcels arm.
The draft, which was due to be published in the next few weeks, is
understood to have leaned heavily in favour of Mr Heseltine's plans to
privatise 51 per cent of the Post Office, leaving the remainder of the stock
in government hands.
But, according to one Whitehall official, Mr Major has told Mr Heseltine
that the document does not give sufficient weight to the option of leaving
the Post Office completely in the public domain - an option backed by many
Tory backbenchers.
A Whitehall official said yesterday: 'The hope is that that the green paper
would have something in it other than the privatisation option. A green
paper is a broad-ranging document and needs to look at absolutely
everything.'
The setback to Mr Heseltine's plans comes amid growing uncertainty among
Tory MPs about whether the Post Office should be sold.
A number of Conservative MPs believe the organisation has a crucial social
function and that its privatisation would be highly unpopular with the
public.
But rightwing MPs - who are backed on this issue by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor - are urging the government to press ahead with privatisation.
Government business managers have warned ministers that as a result of these
differences it may be difficult to guarantee the passage of a privatisation
bill through the next session of parliament.
Mr Major's decision to block the green paper is the latest blow to Mr
Heseltine's plans for the Post Office.
Originally, Mr Heseltine had wanted to privatise the entire Royal Mail and
Parcelforce but was urged to accept only a partial sell-off.
Mr Heseltine has since made a range of concessions to backbench MPs,
including a commitment to universal tariffs and the exemption of stamps from
value added tax.
</TEXT>
