<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Idyllic fortress ready to lower drawbridge: Tiny Alderney is
a victim of its own success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNY LUESBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Alderney in the Channel Islands has run out of money, which is no mean feat
for an island where Lloyd's Names make up nearly 2 per cent of the
population and almost half the residents are independently wealthy.
For decades the island has thrived as the fulfilment of an idyll. Alderney
has its own parliament, civil service, airport, hospital, golf course,
sailing club, newspaper and banks - and fewer than 2,400 residents. All the
inhabitants and institutions are squeezed into an island just 3 1/2 miles
long by 1 1/2 miles wide without damaging the rhythm of rural life.
But the island's very success in selling itself as a haven from the 20th
century has been its undoing.
Residents who have chosen to live in Alderney because of its peace and
seclusion have fought to preserve it from change, just as others have sought
to increase their prosperity and comfort through further development.
This conflict of interest came to a head five years ago when
conservationists united against a local entrepreneur's proposal to reopen a
granite quarry.
The dispute was bitter for an island renowned for its friendliness and
goodwill, spilling over into demonstrations and boycotts. But the campaign
was successful and the quarry scheme was cancelled.
This success boosted the preservation lobby and was rapidly followed by
measures to slow the property market, which had continued to flourish as
that of the UK declined. The island's States, or parliament, introduced a
100 per cent property tax on profits made by selling a house within five
years of its purchase.
Investors stopped buying houses on Alderney, and so did many people looking
for second homes or towards a future retirement on the island. In just two
years, the revenue from the local property transaction tax, known as conge,
was halved.
More measures followed. Legislation was adopted to prevent the sale of new
houses to settlers. And the more outspoken conservationists started pushing
to turn the island's village centre, St Anne, into a conservation area.
The effect of pulling up the drawbridge against future settlers and of
limiting change and development on the island was to tie Alderney's fortunes
inextricably to those of its existing settlers.
Last year the combined effect of the Lloyd's syndicates' losses and falling
interest rates saw Alderney's income-tax revenue fall 18 per cent. The
deficit ate much of the island's capital reserve account, built up from past
surpluses. This year's projected deficit seems set to finish the job,
forcing Alderney to turn to Guernsey to make up the shortfall.
Since 1948 Guernsey has provided Alderney's core services under a deal
designed to help the islanders on their return to an island devastated
during the second world war. Alderney levies its taxes at Guernsey rates and
passes the revenue to Guernsey, which charges for the services it provides
before allowing Alderney to manage the surplus.
Alderney, like the other Channel Islands, is not constitutionally part of
the UK. It is part of the bailiwick of Guernsey, which is itself a Crown
possession. The governor of Guernsey is also governor of Alderney, but
Alderney's parliament petitions directly to the Privy Council.
Alderney and Guernsey also levy the same taxes, and Alderney passes its tax
revenue to Guernsey in return for the provision of core services. Because of
this agreement, two members of the States of Alderney represent the island
in the Guernsey States of Deliberation, or parliament.
Alderney's external affairs and treaties come under the jurisdiction of the
British parliament and are handled by the UK's Foreign Office.
Alderney is bound by EU external trade arrangements and agricultural
policies. But it is not affected by EU taxation, employment or any other
policy area.
A clause in the 1948 deal between Alderney and Guernsey, all but forgotten
until this year's financial crisis, obliges Guernsey to cover a deficit from
its own funds when Alderney cannot meet its expenses. Nevertheless, Alderney
cannot rely on Guernsey to go on subsidising it.
As Mr George Baron, Alderney's president, points out, no agreement is
binding for ever, and there is every chance that Guernsey and Alderney would
be forced to consider an alternative arrangement if the deficit continued.
Meanwhile, Alderney cannot raise its income tax rate from Guernsey's 20 per
cent, and if it cuts its services it may deter the present and future
settlers on whom it depends for its revenue. In 1992 income tax accounted
for more than two-thirds of Alderney's revenue. With preservation so
recently the order of the day, Alderney has been left with only one choice,
and that is to develop the island to increase its income.
Mr Baron said: 'Either we accept change, or we lose our autonomy.' And
Alderney has started to accept change. Six months ago the elections for the
presidency and four seats on the 12-member States swept away the
conservationist majority. The property tax law was promptly overturned, and
recent months have seen a flurry of development schemes.
The island has long been deadlocked over whether it should build a marina
which would provide protection from the north and north-easterly winds that
the natural harbour lacks. A consensus is forming in favour of this.
The States has launched a competitive tender for the Pounds 8m redevelopment
of one of the Victorian forts that ring the island - and it is no longer
confining its possible uses to activities as low-key as, perhaps, a study
centre. It might be a hotel. It might even house a casino.
And the mood is for more houses that can be sold to settlers or islanders,
on an island which is changing and developing in an effort to balance its
need for conservation against its need for revenue.
</TEXT>
