<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Job prospects 'best for four years'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The most optimistic outlook for job prospects for four years is reported
today in the latest survey by Manpower UK, the recruitment organisation.
No region is forecasting job cuts in the three months to September, with the
east Midlands remaining the most positive for the second successive quarter.
London continues to show a marked improvement in job prospects - last year
it was the most pessimistic. Only the north-west and Scotland are
forecasting a worse position than in the same period last year.
The survey, which is based on responses from 2,165 employers, showed 26 per
cent of employers forecasting job increases and 11 per cent forecasting job
losses, resulting in a positive net balance of 15 per cent.
The manufacturing sector is the most optimistic about job prospects.
Significant jobs growth is also forecast in the building sector, with the
private building sector forecasting the greatest increase in jobs over any
industry covered by the survey. The public sector remains the weakest, with
local government still affected by the large increase in contracted out
services.
Ms Lilian Bennett, head of Manpower UK, said: 'There is still a sharp focus
by managers on increased productivity, improvement of quality standards and
greater flexibility of labour, which augurs well for the fourth quarter.'
Employment Prospects. Manpower, International House, 66 Chiltern Street,
London W1M IPR.
</TEXT>
