<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Merseyside companies increase turnover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Research into the performance of privately-owned, medium-sized companies in
the recession has uncovered unexpected resilience, with turnover and profits
growing steadily and the number of employees increasing.
The work has been done on Merseyside, one of Britain's most
economically-distressed areas, which is getting more than Pounds 600m of EU
special funding in the next six years to try to catch up with average
European performance.
The Liverpool office of KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy firm, has
analysed the filed results of 993 unquoted independent companies in
Merseyside and the local contributions of 551 subsidiaries of national or
international companies.
A majority - 852 independents and 340 subsidiaries - are small, with sales
of less than Pounds 5m a year each. Most sales were generated by the 141
independents and 211 subsidiaries turning over more than Pounds 5m each.
Their combined sales figures totalled Pounds 10.85bn in 1992-93, compared
with Pounds 9.17bn two years earlier.
Among the 141 medium-sized and large independents aggregate turnover rose
nearly 18 per cent over three years - from nearly Pounds 2.1bn in 1990-91 to
nearly Pounds 2.5bn in 1992-93. Profits grew 57 per cent over the three
years - from Pounds 54m in 1990-91 to Pounds 85m in 1992-93.
Shareholders' funds rose 29 per cent to Pounds 488m, so corporate net worth
improved. So did the number of jobs, with the 141 independent companies
employing 21,997 in 1992-93 compared with 20,951 in 1990-91.
Mr Tim Beer, who is setting up a north-west regional unit for KPMG dealing
only with owner-managed businesses, said yesterday: 'Medium-sized companies
based on Merseyside have been able to weather the storm of the recession,
possibly better than other sectors or areas of the UK.
</TEXT>
