FT  13 JUN 94 / Kyrgyzstan 'needs Russia'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Askar Akayev, the reformist president of the poor and remote republic of
Kyrgyzstan, was quoted at the weekend as saying that his country was doomed
by its backwardness to return to Russia's economic orbit, Leyla Boulton
reports. According to the Russian Information Agency, President Akayev, in a
surprisingly frank description of his nation's prospects, said its industry
could not attract 'serious' foreign investment and would remain 'on the
sidelines of economic progress' for at least 10 to 15 years.
