<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Scandinavians relieved as Austrians vote Yes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Austria's unequivocal vote to join the European Union brought a big sigh of
relief above all among the leaders of fellow EU applicants Finland, Norway
and Sweden.
All three Nordic governments face deep scepticism or, in the case of Norway,
outright hostility to the proposal to accompany Austria into the union from
January 1 next year.
Signs last week that opposition to membership was mounting in Austria had
raised fears that a No vote would further entrench opposition in the north.
But there was also a hope last night that the wide margin of the Austrian
Yes vote would give a long-awaited lift to Nordic EU supporters, who have
struggled to impart any momentum so far to their campaigns for similar
referendums which are to be held in Finland in October and in Sweden and
Norway in November.
Mr Pertti Salolainen, Finland's foreign trade minister, said the outcome
could help push Finnish voters towards the Yes campaign. 'This piece of news
is very positive and I am very happy about it. . . I'm a believer in the
so-called domino theory.'
Mr Carl Bildt, the Swedish prime minister, said the Austrian result was an
'important signal' for Sweden's referendum.
He said the outcome showed that the argument he had made strongly - that
Sweden must be inside the EU to exert any influence over the future
political and economic development of Europe - was decisive.
He was able to say with genuine conviction that 'country after country' now
sought to participate in European co-operation.
Mrs Gro Harlem Brundtland, the Norwegian prime minister facing a No campaign
with well over 50 per cent support in the opinion polls, made much the same
point. She also said Austrian entry to the EU strengthened the opportunity
to build bridges between western and eastern Europe. The Norwegian No
campaign has argued that the EU will shut out poorer former eastern bloc
countries.
The Austrian yes vote comes just before three important party congresses on
the EU issue in Finland, Norway and Sweden next weekend.
In Finland, Mr Esko Aho, prime minister, must overcome deep concern about
the effect of membership on the country's heavily-subsidised farmers when he
seeks the formal backing of his rurally-based Centre party for joining the
EU.
It should also stiffen the ranks of his coalition government in a difficult
parliamentary no-confidence vote due on Wednesday.
The Austrian result will reinforce, too, the leaderships of Mrs Brundtland's
Labour party and the Swedish opposition Social Democratic party as they hold
special conferences to fix party policy on the EU issue. Both are expected
to win party support despite heavy internal opposition.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
