<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Right makes strong gains on Continent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative parties in Germany, Italy and Spain swept to victory in
yesterday's European parliament elections, although the rightwing
government's score in France was badly dented by strong support for
anti-Maastricht dissidents.
Across the 12 European Union nations that voted in the elections for the
567-member assembly yesterday and on June 9, rightwing gains on the
Continent were offset by Labour's landslide win in the UK.
As a result, the relative strengths of the parties in the enlarged
Strasbourg assembly appear likely to be little changed compared with the old
518-seat parliament.
In the eight countries that voted for the parliament yesterday, Mr Helmut
Kohl, the German chancellor, emerged as the main victor, according to
computer projections. These indicated an unexpected triumph for Mr Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union and a considerable setback for the opposition
Social Democratic party, in what was virtually a dress rehearsal of
Germany's general election in October.
Computer projections on Germany's two main public television channels showed
the CDU and its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union, gaining
support in the European poll to almost 40 per cent, compared with 37.7 per
cent in the previous poll five years ago.
In contrast, the SPD, which was ahead in opinion polls until only weeks ago,
looked set to suffer its worst result since the first direct elections to
the European parliament in 1979.
General solid support for Christian Democrat parties on the Continent hit
socialist hopes of sweeping gains in the parliament in Strasbourg.
According to projections early this morning, based on provisional results
from all 12 EU nations, the Socialist group and likely allies at Strasbourg
assembly will have 213 seats compared with 197 in the outgoing parliament.
The Christian Democratic group and its allies will have 178 seats against
the previous 162.
Far-right parties did well in Italy and Belgium, while political
fragmentation was evident above all in France, where both left and rightwing
parties suffered from a sharp swing to two maverick groupings.
France's anti-Maastricht Another Europe list, led by renegade conservative
Mr Philippe de Villiers and Sir James Goldsmith, the Anglo-French tycoon,
won more than 12 per cent of the vote, according to Interior Ministry
figures.
The Radical Energy group led by Mr Bernard Tapie, the controversial football
boss, also took about 12 per cent, drawing away support from the opposition
Socialist party, which saw its share fall to 15 per cent from 23.6 per cent
in 1989.
In Italy, computer projections indicated sharp gains for prime minister
Silvio Berlusconi's Forza Italia party, projected to score more than 30 per
cent, up 9 percentage points from the March general election.
Italy's neo-fascist MSI-National Alliance achieved about 12.5 per cent,
compared with 13.5 per cent in the March general election.
Governing Christian Democrat parties achieved stronger than expected scores
in Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg. The party's resilient showing in
those countries and in Germany may strengthen support for European
integration among EU 'core' members.
On the other hand, support for parties that oppose or are sceptical about
Maastricht in France and Italy, two traditional supporters of European
unity, underlined the confusion about the future of European co-operation.
In Ireland, the Greens won their first European parliament seat and were
poised to snatch a second, although the main victor was prime minister
Albert Reynolds's Fianna Fail.
The left suffered a drubbing in Spain, where the Socialist party of prime
minister Felipe Gonzalez lost ground heavily to the opposition conservative
Popular party. The Spanish Socialists' vote fell to its lowest point since
they came to power in 1982.
The governing centre-right PDS party of prime minister Anibal Cavaco Silva
was dealt a setback in Portugal, while Greece's governing Socialist
Panhellenic Socialist Movement looked set to win that country's vote.
In Belgium, the party of prime minister Jean-Luc Dehaene looked set to
remain the leading political group.
Early results in Luxembourg's general election, which was also held
yesterday, pointed to prime minister Jacques Santer's Social Christian party
remaining the biggest in parliament.
