<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Austria links its future to Union in strong turnout: 66.4%
Yes vote in referendum gives big boost to EU confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER and HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA, STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Austrians yesterday gave the European Union its first big vote of confidence
in several years, with 66.4 per cent voting in a national referendum in
favour of joining the Union.
The turnout for the referendum, 81 per cent, was equally impressive, in
contrast to the low participation in European parliamentary elections in
many countries yesterday.
Late in the afternoon, when the scale of the result became known,
enthusiastic crowds waving EU flags gathered at main political party
headquarters in Vienna and in front of the federal chancellery shouting, 'We
are the champions'.
Mr Alois Mock, the Austrian foreign minister, said: 'It proves that
Austrians are determined to play their part in building the new Europe.'
It is also a boost for pro-EU forces in Norway, Sweden and Finland where EU
entry referendums are due in the autumn. The wide margin of victory of the
Austrian Yes vote brought hope of a long-awaited lift to Nordic EU
supporters who have struggled to impart any momentum so far to their
campaigns.
More immediately, the Austrian Yes vote comes before three important party
congresses on the EU issue in Finland, Norway and Sweden next weekend, and a
parliamentary no-confidence vote due on Wednesday in Finland.
Mr Carl Bildt, the Swedish prime minister, welcomed the Austrian decision
last night as 'an important signal' to Swedes. 'That the result was so
strong was based upon the wish to influence the development of Europe. The
argument for influence won, and won big,' Mr Bildt said.
Only in Finland, where fear of neighbouring Russia is a major factor, is the
Yes campaign leading the referendum race in the opinion polls. In Sweden and
especially in Norway, the No campaigns hold a strong lead.
Mrs Gro Harlem Brundtland, the Norwegian prime minister facing a No campaign
with well over 50 per cent support in the opinion polls, said Austrian entry
to the EU strengthened the opportunity to build bridges between western and
eastern Europe. The Norwegian No campaign had argued that the EU would shut
out poorer former eastern bloc countries.
The Austrian vote will be well received by the country's central European
neighbours. The Czech republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Poland and Slovenia all
hope that their interest in joining the EU will be taken up by Brussels soon
after the current applicants become members.
Respectable majorities in every province in Austria backed EU entry. Even in
Tyrol, where resentment over pollution from alpine lorry transit has
provoked strong anti-EU sentiment, the majority Yes vote was 56.4 per cent.
The handsome scale of the national majority raises questions about the
accuracy of opinion polls in the past week, which indicated a very close
race.
Government officials said yesterday their own polls showed many people were
shaken by scare stories put out late in the campaign by the anti-EU camp. It
was claimed, for example, that Austria, once it joined the EU, would have to
supply water to Spain and could be forced to build nuclear power stations.
Anti-EU campaigners, led by Mr Jorg Haider, the populist rightwing leader of
the Austrian Freedom party, combined these stories with posters recommending
that if people had any doubts they should vote No.
But late last week, the pro-EU camp responded strongly, dismissing the scare
stories and emphasising the importance of the vote for the country's future
security and prosperity.
Austrian leaders plan to sign their accession treaty at the EU summit in
Corfu on June 24. The country then becomes an official observer of EU
institutions from July 1 until its official entry on January 1 1995.
Opponents' scare campaign turns tide in Austrian referendum, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ATZ  Austria, West Europe.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
    FIZ  Finland, West Europe.
    NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
