<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Austria votes decisively to join Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER and HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA, STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Austrians yesterday gave the European Union its first big vote of confidence
in several years, with 66.4 per cent voting in a national referendum in
favour of joining the Union.
The turnout for the referendum, 81 per cent, was equally impressive and by
late afternoon crowds waving EU flags gathered at the main party
headquarters in Vienna and at the federal chancellery shouting: 'We are the
champions'.
Mr Alois Mock, the Austrian foreign minister, said: 'It proves that
Austrians are determined to play their part in building the new Europe.' The
wide margin of victory was also a boost for pro-EU forces in Norway, Sweden
and Finland where EU entry referendums are due in the autumn. The Austrian
vote comes before party congresses on the EU in the three countries and a
parliamentary no-confidence vote on Wednesday in Finland.
Mr Carl Bildt, Swedish prime minister, welcomed Austria's decision as 'an
important signal' to Swedes. Only in Finland is the Yes campaign leading the
race in the opinion polls.
Mrs Gro Harlem Brundtland, Norway's premier, facing a No campaign with over
50 per cent support in the polls, said Austrian entry strengthened the
bridge-building between western and eastern Europe.
Austria's official entry will be on January 1 1995.
Scare campaign, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
