<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Clinton tightens screw on Haiti
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Images of war cemeteries, military bands and proud old veterans have
surrounded President Bill Clinton for the last week, but they have done
little to change the unfriendly landscape that awaited him on his return
from Europe to Washington.
Yesterday Mr Clinton announced tighter sanctions against Haiti - an end to
all commercial flights and a ban on private financial transactions - but
foreign policy difficulties in Haiti still fester as in North Korea and
Bosnia.
In a Gallup poll conducted for CNN and USA Today, only 49 per cent of those
questioned found Mr Clinton honest and trustworthy, although 78 per cent
thought him 'a nice guy.'
As he approaches three crucial weeks before the July 4 congressional recess
candidates from his own Democratic party continue to distance themselves
from him, and even the Democratic National Committee's political director
acknowledged 'there are clearly some areas of the country where it's not
going to benefit a candidate to associate himself with Bill Clinton' - a
remark swiftly repudiated by the White House.
Next week, the president is expected to unveil his proposals for 'ending
welfare as we know it,' a plan built around limiting benefits from the Aid
to Families with Dependent Children programme, the cornerstone of the US
social safety net, to two years.
But the ambitious reform programme is probably stalled until next year as it
must take second place on the legislative agenda to health care reform,
making only slow progress. Mr Clinton faces a decision on how soon to
involve himself in the struggle. Until now, the White House has left the
Congress to fight over the details.
The battle of health care has not been made any easier by the indictment of
Congressman Dan Rostenkowski, formerly chairman of the ways and means
committee, on charges of fraud and embezzlement. He was arraigned in court
yesterday, and pleaded not guilty.
Mr Clinton's own legal travails have not gone away. He will soon have to
respond to the charges of sexual harassment filed against him by a former
Arkansas state employee. Congressional hearings on his investment in the
Whitewater property venture are also expected next month.
</TEXT>
