<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Lara's theme becomes a symphony: Dominic Lawson describes
how he learned - the hard way - to judge fine cricket talent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINIC LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was January 1991. We were on holiday in the West Indies. I discovered
that, on a day too hot for sunbathing, a West Indian under-21 team was
playing a three-day cricket match against a touring Australian XI on the
island of St Vincent.
I persuaded my wife that we should take the little boat across to watch the
game: the locals said we really should go, if only to see a youth called
Brian Lara, whom they considered to be their most promising player since the
young Gary Sobers.
The ground on the tiny island was so primitive that there were not even
turnstiles or tickets. A man would simply stamp a 'pass' mark on the wrists
of those who paid to enter. While we were there, Lara scratched around for
20 or so runs before being caught in the covers.
I turned to my wife, and said, with all the authority of half-an-hour's
knowledge: 'I don't think this man Lara's all he's cracked up to be.'
Don't forget: you read it here first.
We are still in danger of underestimating the achievements of Brian Lara, in
the week that the little man has scored 501 not out, in a single innings
over a day and a bit, setting a record which, unless we return to timeless
Test matches, is unlikely ever to be broken.
The skill and strength involved in taking 390 runs off a first-class bowling
attack in a single day is almost unimaginable, and because of that, not
properly appreciated.
To the wider public it resembles a party trick, a magician's sleight of
hand. It needs to be put in the context of the game as a whole, rather than
a few other freakish achievements by Don Bradman or Gary Sobers.
If you play club or village cricket you will understand what I mean. The
best batsman in that game is, in that context, an impressive sight. He will
hit the ball ferociously, and probably score 100 runs against club players
you thought were rather good. The chances are that he once played for a
county second XI, when he was in his prime. But he was not good enough to be
a professional, let alone command a regular place in an English county's
first XI.
Imagine what a regular county player would do to your club's bowlers. But
even that player does not register more than a couple of points on the
cricketing Richter scale. Compared to a player selected for the England team
he is a plodding trundler, non-descript, untalented even. Then, imagine the
speed of co-ordination of the best batsmen in the England team, and attempt
to realise that, on a purely statistical calculation, they are several times
less good than Brian Lara.
Television is the medium through which the public appreciates the skills of
the first-class cricketer, the medium through which most people will witness
the genius of Lara.
But television hopelessly underestimates that genius. There is no sense,
through the foreshortened picture from the camera at the end of the ground,
of the fantastic speed of the ball, as it travels towards - and sometimes
away from - the batsman.
From the armchair sportsman's perspective, the batsman edging a ball into
the slips looks almost deliberately incompetent and the slip fielder who
drops the catch, sluggish beyond belief.
The same perspective, to a lesser extent, is shared by the man in the
stands, say 200 yards from the action; hence my fatuous remarks about Brian
Lara, when I watched him play more than three years ago in St Vincent.
But not much more than a year ago, I learned my lesson. I found myself
playing cricket in a testimonial match for the West Indian fast bowler
Courtney Walsh. By some strange chance I got him out.
When it was my turn to bat, Courtney grabbed the ball. Three times he
bowled, and three times I saw nothing. I just heard a percussive thump as
the ball hit the pitch and another thump as, a split second later, the ball
had travelled a further 20 yards into the wicket-keeper's gloves.
Courtney was not bowling his fastest, of course not, he did not want to hurt
me. He was probably bowling at the sort of pace which Brian Lara can hit at
a rate of almost 400 runs a day.
Dominic Lawson is editor of The Spectator.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
