<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Lunch with the FT: The billionaire grocer - Michael
Thompson-Noel raises the subject of money with David Sainsbury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the richest people in Britain is sitting opposite me and has just
started his main course: piccatas of veal with courgettes, tomatoes and
olives. The British, he says, do not appreciate veal sufficiently.
For his starter, my billionaire guest had chicken and goat's cheese mousse.
And in a little while - no pudding - he will drink a single cup of filter
coffee before saying goodbye and going to look for his driver.
We are enjoying our chat, although I have not yet raised the subject of
money. I have held myself back - anxious, I suppose, to demonstrate
sensitivity for someone whose wealth is so ginormous that the noughts on the
end of it swirl round and round our heads.
This is David Sainsbury, 53, chairman and chief executive of J. Sainsbury,
Britain's leading grocery chain. In the 1994 edition of The Sunday Times
survey of Britain's richest residents, he and other family members were said
to be worth a combined Pounds 2.7bn - less than Gad and Hans Rausing, the
TetraPak brothers (Pounds 5.2bn), or Queen Elizabeth II (Pounds 5bn), but
comfortably ahead of John and Peter Moores (Pounds 1.7bn), John Paul Getty
II (Pounds 1.65bn), Garfield Weston (Pounds 1.6bn) and the Duke of
Westminster (Pounds 1.5bn).
I have no idea how accurate these estimates are; nor does The Sunday Times.
And I am not about to ask David Sainsbury if he knows, because I am sure he
doesn't. But the subject must be broached, even if obliquely, in the middle
of the piccatas.
'Is it true,' I ask, 'that you personally own 18 per cent of Sainsbury's
shares?' In spite of the recent stock market shake-out, Sainsbury's is still
capitalised at a squeak under Pounds 7bn.
'I think,' he says quietly, 'that it's 17 per cent.'
'Are you aware of your wealth - of how much money there is behind you and
around you?'
He does not mind the question. I have realised, already, that David
Sainsbury, for all his modesty and thoughtfulness, is a master of
directness. Nothing seems to throw him. It is clear, moreover, that he has
come here to talk. He speaks lucidly and treats all questions with
indulgence: a five-star interviewee, though he would be surprised to be told
so.
He has neatly-cropped hair and lightly-framed spectacles, and has been
described, quite accurately, as resembling an Israeli general in mufti.
'The enjoyable thing to do with wealth,' he says, 'is to achieve change.
Awareness of wealth depends on how you are brought up. In those days' - his
childhood - 'Sainsbury's wasn't a public company, so there weren't any
shares. Anyway, my parents taught me that if you had money, you used it for
good purposes. There was never any question about your not working. I am
sure that my upbringing is the reason why I enjoy using my money in
constructive ways.'
He joined the family firm in 1963 and held a succession of posts, including
that of finance director for 17 years to 1990. Then he became deputy
chairman and took over as chairman from his cousin, Lord Sainsbury, late in
1992.
When he became chairman, he told the FT: 'Food retailing is a very dynamic
and a very competitive business. It is a market of changing fortunes. We are
leaders now and it is absolutely my intention to have a bigger lead when I
cease to be chairman. But we will only do so by changing our business. I am
certain we will be a very different business in 10 years' time.'
He lives modestly and is not at all interested in the trappings of wealth.
In January 1993 he donated Pounds 200m worth of Sainsbury's shares to his
philanthropic vehicle, the Gatsby Charitable Foundation, a grant-making
trust which he established and has funded since 1967. The donation was
easily the biggest of its kind in living memory. The trust's activities
include technical education, African development programmes, economic and
business research, support for disadvantaged children, health care and plant
science.
We met at the Kensington Place restaurant in Notting Hill, west London. It
is bright, noisy, hip and crucial - renowned for serving a mixture of modern
brasserie food and more classical dishes cooked with immense flair. You can
have a set three-course lunch for Pounds 13.50: probably the best-value
lunch in town.
The Sainsbury's chairman told me that he used to be a regular at Kensington
Place a couple of years ago. 'Then I stopped, and then I started again,
about a month ago, and remembered how much I enjoyed it.'
If he had not been born a Sainsbury, what would he have become?
'Well,' he said, 'I studied history first, at Cambridge, and then
psychology, and there was a time when I thought I'd do research in
psychology: brain studies, perception, that sort of thing. Then I decided
that I'd make a much better businessman. But science, especially cognitive
neuro-science, has become so remarkably interesting . . .'
'You're not religious?'
'No.'
'So you're not worried about looking for the soul?'
'No. But that is not to say that human consciousness is not still totally
mysterious. And there is still, for me, a distinction to be drawn between
human consciousness and computer intelligence.'
After a few years' work for the family firm, he studied for an MBA at
Columbia University, New York, and then threw himself once more into
high-powered grocery retailing.
'The great attraction of business - particularly of retailing - is that
there is a very clear relationship between what you do and the end product.
It's very hands-on. You get instant feed-back. With politics, in contrast,
it is very unclear what actually results from what you do.
'I get real pleasure from visiting our stores. I could also get real
pleasure from running a factory.'
'A factory? Really? I detest them.'
'It's the challenge of integrating people and product flows so as to achieve
something worthwhile that fascinates me.'
I said: 'Could I go out there this afternoon' - I pointed to the high street
 -'and lay down the foundations of a retail chain that would eventually grow
as large as your great-grandfather's business has become today? Could I do
that?'
'Yes,' said the billionaire grocer, 'though you couldn't just launch a chain
of supermarkets. People seldom realise how complicated our business has
become. That is its challenge: to bring an enormous range of products from
all over the world into a specific place and to sell them so as to meet
predicted demand at a particular price.
'For example, we are bringing in skate from the US. Americans don't like
skate. They throw it in the harbour. But we are using new-technology packs
that enable us to bring this skate into Britain.'
Does he like food? 'Yes. It has always been a passion for the whole family.
You should only work in businesses where you have great regard for the
product. Play-back is essential. I was finance director for all those years,
yet you can only get so far on the figures or, indeed, on market research.'
'Do you cook?'
'Only bachelor cooking.'
'I was surprised,' I said, 'at Sainsbury's recent contretemps with Coca-Cola
caused by your selling a look-alike own-label cola that Coke claimed
resembled, in the appearance of its packaging, its own product far too
closely. One thinks of Sainsbury's as excessively well behaved. Why did you
get into such a scrape?'
The billionaire did not flinch. He said: 'Fifty-five per cent of our
(packaged grocery) sales are own-label. We have always been in the business
of finding better-value products than the branded ones. For the first time,
a cola has been found that is as good as Coca-Cola. This is a new situation
for Coke. The issue of the tin is, frankly, rather irrelevant.'
'But what about your behaviour? Suppose someone came along and helped
themselves to a bit of Sainsbury's glamour, or Sainsbury's expertise -
something established over a great many years - and stuck it on to their
product. Would you be happy?'
'They've done that,' said the chairman. 'Sainsbury's own-label wine
products, for example, have been copied by other people. In the end, the
consumer will decide. Instead of taking a year for everyone to try our cola,
it's taken about two weeks.
'The affair was portrayed as branded product versus own-label. But if you
look just at the branded sector for a moment, you will see that there are
things that designers do all around the world, in terms of packaging.
'One of their design conventions is that red is the colour people associate
with cola tins, so it is hardly surprising that our cola tin resembled
Coke's.
'Anyway,' he said happily, draining his coffee, 'our cola is selling
unbelievably well.'
He smiled. And then he stood - leaving me to reflect that billionaire-style
grocery must be an amusing thing to be in.
</TEXT>
