<PROFILE>_AN-EFLAKAE2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940611
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Travel: An unforgettable night in a room in Mandalay - After
a Chinese meal with a German doctor, Mark Hodson extricates himself from a
tricky situation at the Hotel Venus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK HODSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Burma is not famous for its nightlife, and with just cause. At 9pm the one
TV channel closes down after showing exactly three hours of state propaganda
and marching band music - after which you can wander out and find all the
restaurants shut.
It was a Saturday night in Mandalay, city of kings and Rudyard Kipling. I
was sharing a room at the Hotel Venus with a German doctor and we had eaten
Chinese at Min Min Restaurant followed by strawberries and vanilla scoops at
the Nylon Ice Cream Bar. We would have gone to a bar but there are none.
We returned to the room to find that the air-conditioning had packed up and
the boy downstairs was playing old Rod Stewart videos over the hotel cable
system. We were resigned to another game of chess when there was a knock on
the door and two young Burmese men, grinning and stripped to the waist,
asked if we would like to come next door for a drink. It sounded rather
dubious, so we thought it best to decline.
'We do have some cold beer in the fridge,' one said.
Inside, their room looked like a battle-ground. It was strewn with every
possible discarded bottle and food carton. On each of the two beds sat a
girl in T-shirt, shorts and high heels, both about 17 years old, wearing
gormless grins.
The boys cleared a space for us on one of the beds by sweeping some rubbish
on to the floor. They poured some beer and told us their names, ignoring the
girls, who just giggled. Clearly they had not been invited for their
dazzling conversation.
The boys told us they were in Mandalay to sell rubies. They lived in Mogok,
a mining village in the mountains to the north, an area off-limits to
foreigners. Business, said one, raising a glass, was very good.
I had seen something of the ruby trade at a place called Taung-gyi, about
eight hours out of Mandalay. The gem market on the edge of town was a
raucous den of sharks and smugglers: hill-tribe men, Bangladeshis, Indians
and Chinese.
As I dodged between the tightly-packed stalls where crowds huddled over
piles of uncut stones, I found myself instinctively clutching my money belt.
But in a country so poor and almost entirely deprived of western goods, I
had never seen such ostentatious wealth: chunky gold necklaces, designer
labels, fistfuls of dollars.
As one of the boys topped up my glass the door opened and in walked two
Indian men. One was tall, a little awkward, the other short and powerful,
about 45, with piercing eyes and a face as hard as any I have seen. A
striped green shirt strained to contain his thick arms, and around his neck
hung a thick gold chain. He took us in with a glance, then fired some
questions at the boys in a language I did not recognise. Then he turned to
us with a cruel smile.
'Like these girls?' he asked.
'Very nice,' I said diplomatically. In fact they were quite ugly. Despite
their puppy fat, they looked as though they had worked more nights in seedy
hotel rooms than they had eaten hot dinners. And they were becoming a
nuisance. One had moved behind Axel, the German, and was trying to massage
his shoulders; the other sat beside me with one hand across my leg.
One of the boys asked me: 'Have you used a Burmese lady yet?' I said no. He
asked why not.
'Er, perhaps I haven't met the right girl yet,' I said. I was thinking this
would be a good time to leave when the door opened again and in walked two
more men, a tall bearded Indian and a Burmese boy of about 14 with a shaved
head. It was getting to be quite a party.
The newcomers stood admiring their unexpected guests as we made polite
conversation about the ruby business while I kept one eye on my drink. I was
wondering whether it was spiked, and was keeping a hand on my leg to ward
off the prostitute.
Suddenly, Axel leapt up from the bed as if he had sat on a cattle prod. 'OK,
where is it?' he yelled.
There was silence, and a little nervous fidgeting. 'Someone has got my
wallet. I felt it taken out of my pocket. Now where is it?' Axel was
furious, his voice rising and his German accent thickening.
I thought: I should have seen this coming. Our hosts looked stunned and
indignant, spluttering denials.
Axel moved towards the door, saying: 'No one leaves here until I get it
back.'
I drained the last of my beer and held on to the glass. I knew what had to
be done. I had seen enough movies. I would break the end off the glass and
thrust it into the tough guy's face. What would happen then I had no idea.
Slowly I stood, not scared, just disappointed that an interesting evening
had to end like this. The Burmese boys remained slouched on the other bed,
their grins barely flickering. The hookers seemed to notice nothing amiss.
The three Indians regrouped slightly in the middle of the room and the
skin-head made a dash for the door where Axel stopped him.
Axel was still ranting, the Indians insisting on their innocence. Things
seemed to be coming to a head. I suggested a compromise: Axel would go next
door for two minutes while they had a last look around for the wallet. If it
turned up we would all be friends again, no questions asked.
They agreed. Axel left, while I stood by the door feeling foolish and trying
to act as if this sort of thing happened all the time.
Suddenly, Axel reappeared clutching his wallet. 'So sorry] It was in the
room all along,' he announced with a big smile.
The Indians were furious and the little tough guy ran at us shouting and
swearing in Hindi and English. How dare we insult him, did we not know he
was a very, very rich man?
'Look at this ring,' he said, shaking a fat fist in front of our faces. On
one finger was a band of huge rubies set in gold. My heart sank. I was
filled with shame.
Axel seemed too delighted at recovering his wallet to notice danger. He even
suggested another drink. I tried to cool the situation, explaining that we
were stupid tourists, a little drunk maybe. It had been a long day.
The tough guy was bouncing up and down with rage, veins bulging on his face.
Above all he seemed upset at the implication that he was down on his luck
and needed the money. As Axel grinned, I carried on grovelling.
The tall bearded Indian calmed things down by clutching his chest, saying:
'Oh my God, I was so scared, my heart was going boom, boom, boom. But you
must understand this cheating is not the Burmese way. In India someone will
rob you. In London too. But in Burma - never.'
I knew he was right. The Burmese people were just too sweet-natured. This
was the country where village children blew kisses at tourists instead of
asking for money, and waiters in restaurants used the menus to fan diners as
they ate.
Finally we left, backing out with our tails between our legs, shaking hands
with everyone twice and then a third time. As we fumbled with the door key
the tough guy followed us into the corridor and for a second, fear once
again gripped my stomach.
But his face cracked open with a smile: 'Are you quite sure you don't want
to borrow the girls tonight?'
Return flights to the Burmese capital, Rangoon, from Bangkok cost around
Pounds 150 and it is now possible to fly direct from Chiang Mai in northern
Thailand to Mandalay.
The government of Burma, now renamed Myanmar, has recently been issuing
four-week visas which take two working days to process in Bangkok.
On arrival, foreigners must change Dollars 300 into non-refundable foreign
exchange certificates. However, their value on the black market is almost
the same as cash: around 100 kyats to the dollar, against the official
exchange rate of six.
Burmese hotel standards are acceptable, although most are expensive by Asian
standards.
</TEXT>
