<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Travel: Do not miss Marple, an old Spaghetti Junction - The
Manchester canal network is a cascade of inventiveness on a scale not seen
in Britain since the Romans left
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Had Steven Spielberg lived in England 200 years ago, he might have been a
canal builder. These people used wit, technology and imagination to build
transport systems that - judged by what had gone before - must have seemed
out of this world.
The thought hits you as you stroll along a remarkable stretch of inland
waterway near Marple, a small town on the south-eastern edge of Manchester's
urban sprawl, sited just as the land climbs towards the Pennines.
There is nothing elegant or notable about Marple, the birthplace of
dramatist Christopher Isherwood. Or so you think until you encounter, near
an undistinguished shopping centre, the meeting place, 500ft above sea
level, of three important lengths of canal constructed during the industrial
revolution.
Curving south-east from Marple is the upper branch of the Peak Forest Canal
connecting with the limestone quarries near Buxworth, Derbyshire, four miles
away. The second length is the lower branch of the same canal stretching
north through the Manchester conurbation, while leading off to the
south-west is the Macclesfield Canal linking, eventually, with
Stoke-on-Trent and the Midlands.
In the early 19th century, when the canal system was at its busiest, Marple
must have taken on the character of a watery Spaghetti Junction. Today, with
holiday barges constituting the main traffic, the town's canal area is
quietly picturesque.
From Marple, an attractive walk runs along the towpath of the northern
branch of the Peak Forest canal, past an impressive sequence of 16 locks
that brings the water down 200ft through a horizontal distance of about a
mile. A little after this is the famous Marple aqueduct, built, like the
rest of the Peak Forest system, by Benjamin Outram, who also operated an
ironworks in Derbyshire.
The aqueduct is a test for anyone with vertigo. It takes the canal and
towpath across three arches spanning a gorge above the River Goyt 100ft
below. Notable features are the three circular 'shoulders' pierced above
each arch which reduce the weight of the structure and add decoration. A
similarly pleasant touch is the use of two different colours of gritstone,
yellow and pink, in the upper part of the aqueduct.
After the aqueduct, the route takes you past the occasional mill building
through a wooded, semi-rural setting before the canal hits Romily. Here,
next to the watercourse, you can buy a home-cooked hot meal amazingly
cheaply at the unpretentious Bridge Cafe.
Marple is one stop on a 100-mile network of canals around Manchester mainly
built in the late 18th and early 19th centuries in a cascade of
inventiveness that ended a 1,500-year blight in transport planning. With
railways only a gleam in the eye and most roads little better than dirt
tracks, nothing like the canals had been seen since the Romans left.
The canal building, which reached a peak in the 1790s, was driven by a
strong economic imperative: the need for reliable transport systems to ferry
the goods turned out by the world's first large-scale factories.
Today, the Manchester network, known as the 'Cheshire ring', is largely
intact. It sketches out a rough triangle, linking Manchester in the north,
Hardings Wood near Congleton in the south, and Runcorn in the west. In
hillier parts of the region, the watercourses reduce the need for locks by
following contours, so that on maps they are barely distinguishable from
rivers.
While canal aficionados might insist on hiring a boat to explore the system,
most people will probably not want to go to this trouble. Anyhow, walking
along discrete parts of the network gives you a better idea as to how the
canals fit into their localities.
Anyone interested in the ring will probably want to spend some time in the
centre of Manchester, where public and private money has financed the
cleaning of a large section of waterway, including parts of the Bridgewater,
Rochdale and Ashton canals.
The remains of the Castlefields Roman fort near the new G-Mex exhibition
centre may look a little spoiled - and are very hard to make sense of - but
on the whole the area adds up to an impressive example of urban
regeneration.
Particularly recommended is a one-mile walk along the Rochdale canal through
central Manchester. Taking in a sequence of warehouses and lock keepers'
cottages, it gives an inside-out view to the city which cannot have changed
much over two centuries.
Slightly further to the west is Britain's first length of modern man-made
waterway. A section of the Bridgewater canal, it was opened in 1761 and
connected the coal mines at Worsley, owned by the young Duke of Bridgewater,
to Manchester's city centre. The construction expertise came from the
engineer James Brindley and the surveyor John Gilbert.
Anyone wanting something more rural will probably head for the 20-mile
section of the Bridgewater canal further south, including the route through
pleasant countryside around Dunham and Lymm. Ancient Lymm, virtually sliced
in half by the canal, which cuts through the town square, is especially
worth a visit. Pleasant modern houses have their gardens gently extending to
the canal bank, and some old canal buildings have been converted to a
cruising club.
A little further to the west, the late 20th century intrudes. A massive
bridge takes the M6 motorway over the Bridgewater canal, the River Mersey,
the Manchester ship canal and the A56 road. Unless you are really interested
in concrete technology, you will turn around and head for home.
</TEXT>
