<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Sport: A surprise for the wildlife - FT Ski Expedition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARNIE WILSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Arnie Wilson and Lucy Dicker are trying to ski every day of 1994 on a
round-the-world expedition. This week they have been in Europe.
We scattered marmots as we trudged up towards Mont Gele. They are not used
to skiers at this time of the year. After a winter hibernating, they
normally find the slopes empty until summer skiing begins at the end of
June.
What the marmots did not know was that our presence was part of a rescue act
following the sudden closure of the cable cars due to take us to the
Diablerets Glacier across the valley.
At noon, when the high winds and sleet ruled the glacier out of contention
for our daily ski outing, Anita, the receptionist at the Eurotel hotel,
telephoned two other Swiss summer skiing areas - Saas-Fee and Zermatt. To
our alarm, they were closed too.
There was only one thing for it: a telephone call to Patrick Messeiller,
Verbier's tourist director, interrupting his Sunday lunch. It produced the
promise of a jeep.
Francois-Xavier, our driver, would take us as high as possible up a mountain
track. From here we could walk for half an hour or so, giving us a mile's
skiing - our minimum requirement in an emergency. Once again, for about the
tenth time this year, our bacon had been saved.
Before the bad weather, we had been enjoying the skiing at Diablerets, even
though we had to share it with 500 guides holding their annual ski races.
One run was the most beautifully-groomed piste I had ever encountered. You
only had to think a turn and it happened.
Another run, Audon, was almost four miles long and full of challenges - the
longest, most exhilarating descent we had experienced for weeks.
Earlier, we had enjoyed extensive skiing in fresh snow on Austrian glaciers
at Stubai and Solden, with the wildest and most picturesque at Pitztal and
Kaunertal, where we were again in illustrious company, sharing the slopes
with the Austrian and Swiss national ski teams.
We then faced a 450-mile drive in heavy rain from Austria, across
Switzerland and into France, where we slept at Chamonix, before skiing above
Courmayeur on the Italian side of Mont Blanc. It's all go, this search for
snow.
</TEXT>
