<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Arts: Slow revolution at La Scala - Andrew Clark reviews
'Rigoletto' and 'Elektra' and finds Riccardo Muti hard at work trying to
change corrupt 19th century traditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
While Milan's investigating magistrates have led the drive to clean up
Italian public life, Riccardo Muti has been campaigning to rid La Scala of
corrupt performing practices. As music director of his country's leading
opera house, Muti is finding that traditions in 19th century repertoire are
as ingrained as corruption in politics. Change requires a minor revolution.
The operas of Verdi's middle period form the crux of the battle - works
which course through La Scala's blood, arousing intense audience passions.
No one anticipates the high notes at the end of an aria more eagerly than
the Milanese; none is more ready to applaud the final flourish. Taking his
cue from recent Verdi scholarship (which Italian theatres have been
notoriously slow to acknowledge), Muti has been reminding his compatriots
that most of these display notes were not written by the composer. He also
argues that to interrupt with frequent bursts of applause is to
misunderstand Verdi's quest for dramma in musica.
Muti fired his first tentative shot four years ago when he performed La
traviata without the traditional cuts. But the educative process has only
taken wing in the past month with Rigoletto - the first time this popular
work has been performed at La Scala for 23 years. The display notes were
dropped. The performance followed the New Critical Edition to the letter.
And to propagate his ideas before the premiere, Muti held a televised
masterclass at the Milan Conservatory, during which he quoted Verdi's
letters, gave musical illustrations and explained why he did not want
interruptions for applause.
The fact that the first-night audience respected Muti's wishes is a measure
of his authority. At later performances (I attended the fourth), the
loggionisti were quick to silence any spontaneous applause. Muti wants other
Italian theatres to follow suit, and he will take his own campaign a stage
further in 1996 with Il trovatore. It may not please 'the lovers of vocal
mania', to use Muti's words, but it should lead to a 'less veristic, more
civilised' style of Verdi singing, one which accords with the current
emphasis on historical performance.
My initial reaction to Rigoletto was to regret the absence of those very
practices which lend a unique sense of theatre to Verdi performances at La
Scala. Nevertheless, the potential for a Rigoletto of clean dramatic sweep
was there. The fact that it did not materialise was due to other factors.
Two Wagnerian-length intervals sabotaged the evening's flow: one half-hour
break after the first act should be enough. And if Muti wants dramma in
musica rather than melodramma, he needs a more imaginative, less pictorial
staging.
The period settings of Ezio Frigerio and Franca Squarciapino were
Zeffirellian in scale - a gold baroque interior at the start, stained-glass
windows for the second act and a brick facade for the finale, which had the
Duke waltzing along what looked like the top floor of a derelict warehouse.
The producer, Gilbert Deflo, told the story clearly but all too
conventionally.
The singing was good if unexceptional. Roberto Alagna was the handsome young
Duke, throwing off his top notes with ease but delivering his love song to
Gilda in an unremitting forte, essaying a nice trill at the end of 'Parmi
veder' but scarcely caressing the words. There was little sign of Bellinian
grace, Gigli-like charm - or the swagger of a natural libertine.
Hobbling around like a club-footed Punch, Leo Nucci's Rigoletto captured the
public poison and private soul of the court jester, but the vocal acting
lacked distinction. The young Hungarian soprano Andrea Rost made an ideal
Gilda - innocent, pretty and musical, with a silvery voice reminiscent of
Reri Grist. Dimitri Kavrakos was the innocuous Sparafucile, Mariana
Pentcheva an unsubtle Maddalena. Despite some breathless accompaniments,
Muti's conducting bristled with grandezza and tenderness.
The other late-season production has been Elektra. La Scala always used to
import its Strauss from Germany, making sure Wolfgang Sawallisch was
available to guarantee the musical quality. This time it entrusted a new
staging to Italians. Giuseppe Sinopoli conducted - lumpily, sluggishly. Luca
Ronconi and his designers, Gae Aulenti and Giovanna Buzzi, seemed unsure
what to do with the piece. Mycenae had the trappings of a modern abattoir.
Chrysothemis and Klytemnestra wore bare-breasted feather gowns. Elektra was
reduced to a war of the bitches.
Hanna Schwarz's Klytemnestra made every word count, but was too svelte and
noble for the guilt-ridden queen. As Chrysothemis, Sabine Hass shrieked
round the stage like a hysterical bird. Gabriele Schnaut's Elektra was tame
and prosaic. The whole performance lacked tension, menace and momentum.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7929 Entertainers and Entertainment Groups.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
