<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Arts: Romantics from the north - Reinhart Foundation
exhibition at the National Gallery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM PACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Romanticism is one of those useful terms of critical labelling that means
just what we choose it to mean. It may be no more than a mood or attitude -
a long cloak, a wide hat and a dark look. Precisely applied, it invokes the
refinement and self-conscious celebration of sensibility that found
particular expression from the 1770s on, the age of Goethe, Byron,
Beethoven, Gericault, Delacroix, Turner . . .
In taking us from Friedrich to Hodler and into the 20th century, A Romantic
Tradition at the National Gallery seems to want it both ways. At the start,
with Wolf we have the celebration of nature and the sublime, with Friedrich
himself the yearning melancholy of heightened feeling, with Fuseli all the
melodrama of sturm und drang. At the end, with Bocklin and Hodler, we have
sexual symbolism and incipient expressionism. And in between we have a lot
of interesting, unfamiliar and lovely works that are Romantic only if we say
they are. To trace the evolution of early 19th-century Romanticism into
fin-de-siecle symbolism would be as good a peg as any on which to hang an
exhibition, but it would require either a broader international scope than
this admits, or a sharper critical focus.
As it is, the exhibition is limited to the northern European schools,
principally German and Swiss with the odd Dane and Norwegian, by the very
nature of the Reinhart collections. Its positive virtue - and it is indeed a
lovely exhibition - lies rather, and paradoxically, in its uncritical
miscellaneity. We are in this country grievously unfamiliar with the later
northern European schools. The National Gallery has long recognised the
deficiency in its own collections and has begun to repair it - but only
begun: the constraints of our funding policies are ever to be endured. The
chance to see this range of work, to recognise masters hitherto unknown to
us, to take them as they come and to draw fresh comparisons is most welcome.
Friedrich himself is now familiar enough, but his works here are especially
fine and, beside his usual images of setting suns and distant towers,
fraught with the religious symbolism of our path through life, includes more
straight-forward and cheerful landscapes, most remarkable the vertiginous
view down the chalk cliffs at Rugen, which he and his wife visited on their
honeymoon in 1818. No less remarkable, and rather more to the point, are the
looming mountains and glaciers of the 18th century painter, Caspar Wolf, all
painted in the 1770s, the decade of Friedrich's birth.
The Swiss, Jacques-Laurent Agasse, who studied with David in Paris in the
1780s and spent much of his career in England - the Tate rescued him from
our ignorance a year or two ago - features prominently. His affinity with
Stubbs in particular, that famous Romantic, and English sporting and genre
Realism in general, is manifest. It is Agasse who establishes the thread of
Realism that runs through the show, and bourgeois or Biedermeier Realism at
that. The connection with Victorian anecdotal painting, the pre-Raphaelites
and later Social Realism throughout Europe - Ring, Guthrie, Bastien-Lepage -
is easy to sustain.
There are 'The Village Politicians' of Wilhelm Liebel (1877); the portraits
and domestic groups of Albert Anker, notably the large and delightful Creche
(1890), in which a host of children is given soup by a young and beautifully
serious deaconess; the mid-century landscapes of Zund, Koller and Calame;
the looser proto-expressionist studies of Carl Blechen in the 1820s and 30s.
Most remarkable and beautiful of all is the Dane, Christen Kobke's view of a
sailing party just returned (1839), the sail furled, the wind dropped and
the evening coming on, and all so still and febrile in its clarity.
There is much else to recommend, and the works on paper, shown separately in
the Sunley Room, are not to be missed, most especially the pastels and
gouaches of Adolph von Menzel. A fine woman sits with her arms folded, her
eyes shaded by her straw hat, a strong image beautifully realised. It was
made up from a note taken on a boat-trip. The sketchbook source, we are
told, shows that the poor woman, shortly before, had been violently sick.
There is Romantic for you.
Caspar David Friedrich to Ferdinand Hodler: A Romantic Tradition - 19th
century paintings and drawings from the Oskar Reinhart Foundation,
Winterthur; the National Gallery, Trafalgar Square WC2, until September 4,
then on to Geneva.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
