<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Arts: Brecht par excellence - A look at a new, exciting
'Threepenny Opera'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACKIE WULLSCHLAGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Play it as cabaret, and it swoons with ragtime nostalgia. As theatre, it is
sharp, anti-bourgeois satire. As a musical, it is easy escapism. It can be
sentimental, witty or a critique on German society: for all these reasons
Brecht's Threepenny Opera is the most popular piece in the German repertory.
The latest staging from the Dresden State Theatre is the most thrilling I
have seen. Its genius is to harness Weill's music to a vivid and original
psychological reading of the play. This adds a new satiric edge to both
songs and drama and pulls them together in tight artistic cohesion.
Given life and form by impeccable ensemble playing and a set which is pure
theatrical magic, it is vintage Brecht and proof that the Brechtian
traditions which inspired East German theatre for decades are still
thriving.
What a revelation to see Brecht's characters taken beyond the usual
stereotypes - the whore, Jenny, the criminal, Mack the Knife, the innocent
girl, Polly - into rounded, changing people whose relationships drive the
action. Best is Polly, played with every nerve and muscle by Anna-Katherina
Muck. At first, she is a God-fearing girl hardly able to breathe for the
ecstasy of marrying in a (stolen) white open-top Trabby, decked-out with
plastic flowers.
During her wedding night, saxophones and trumpets ominously whirr and
wind-down as if their batteries had run out; the next day, Mack flees. In a
snatch at worldly wisdom, Polly sings one of Jenny's songs; the orchestral
accompaniment - jazzy, up-beat, naive for Polly, languorous and resentful
for Jenny - plays out the mocking contrast.
Back home, her toddler-tantrum - chubby legs flying, stockings falling down
 -as she boasts to her parents of her husband's underworld connections, is
the spur for the Peachums to get Mack hanged. The emotional point is that
she has married her father. Peachum, the Beggar King (Hans Jorn Weber) and
Mack the Knife (Michael Neuenschwander) are both giant, charismatic figures,
slick dressers and smooth talkers, one controlling his crooks, the other his
paupers, with the same menacing flick-of-the-wrist or twist-of-the-head. The
political point, that both are profiteers in collusion with the state, is
here a sub-text.
Against a stunning tower-block set, the power game works as a formally
choreographed dance. A siren shriek and a dozen secret brick-doors burst
open to reveal Mack's criminals, pants down, each hiding in a urinal.
Seconds later, the doors shut and fly open again, each showing a beggar with
his props of wooden legs and eye-patches.
Bathed in purple light, the cubicles next become a brothel which Peachum and
Mack fight to control. Mack sings the Procurer's Ballad pulling up
half-dressed whores from the floor, thrusting at them and then letting them
fall. When one of them sings back in the throaty bass of the Streetsinger,
there is a whiff of real 1920s decadence.
Like the themes of Klaus Dieter Kirst's production, the set keeps opening
out on to new levels. A slice of brickwork vanishes and a beggars' chorus
appears on a neon ramp. Then, a flood of light, the Peachum apartment
shining through a high window and the action leaps to the roof of the stage.
In the finale, beggars, tarts, thugs and policemen, all draped in
fluorescent grey raincoats and carrying umbrellas and wreaths, snake their
way from top to bottom of the set to watch Mack hang. There is the lightest
flurry of snow, then the Streetsinger, wearing archangel wings, arrives by
bicycle to deliver a happy ending. This brought a standing ovation from the
audience at the Brussels Saxony Festival, where I caught this production.
Here is a Threepenny Opera, as Brecht hoped it would be, 'so splendid that
only beggars can imagine it.' Let us hope it visits Britain soon. The
production continues at the Staatschauspiel, Dresden. The Brussels Saxony
Festival runs through June.
</TEXT>
<XX>
