<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Food and Drink: A hearty start to the day - Great British
Eating / Nicholas Lander enjoys a filling and traditional breakfast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS LANDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An American businessman asked a London taxi driver to take him to
Charterhouse Street in the City. Trying to engage his fare in conversation,
the cabbie asked how long the man was staying. 'Not long,' came the reply
'in fact I have just come for breakfast at the Fox &amp; Anchor.'
For the past 100 years the Fox &amp; Anchor has enjoyed a thriving breakfast
trade because of its proximity to early-opening Smithfield meat market. With
a market trading licence, which allows it to sell alcohol outside normal
licensing hours, the pub has been able to serve pints of beer alongside
breakfasts big enough to satisfy the beefiest meat porter.
Smithfield's decline has led to a change in demand. Instead of serving
breakfast at 4am the Fox &amp; Anchor now opens at 7am to serve breakfast and
lunch to those who carry nothing heavier than a briefcase and word
processor. It still serves pints of beer, of course. As we breakfasted, five
young City slickers were meeting in the pub's back room for their 'power
breakfast' and a pint of Guinness.
It seems ironic that demand for the great British breakfast - bacon,
sausage, black pudding, mushrooms, tomatoes and eggs any way you like them -
should prosper because we have now imported the breakfast meeting. Ironic
and slightly comical because nothing could be more difficult than eating
such food - trying to ensure that the fried egg does not drip down your
shirt front - while discussing the finer points of a complicated contract.
Although it is now much easier to buy top quality ingredients for the great
British breakfast (see the accompanying panel), and not suffer watery bacon
or fatty sausage, the meal itself is no less difficult to prepare. Nothing
can be cooked in advance - and no ingredient should be cooked for long.
Getting the timing of these items right is difficult - particularly if you
like your toast hot. Ask any father who, on Mother's Day, has offered to
take over in the kitchen.
I was consoled, therefore, when I turned to the gurus of the great British
breakfast, Francis Coulson and Brian Sack, of Sharrow Bay Hotel in Cumbria,
to hear that, even after 40 years of preparing and supervising breakfast,
the meal is not as simple as it looks.
What makes Sharrow Bay's breakfasts memorable - and two years ago it was
voted the best in the Francophile Relais &amp; Chateaux group - is a combination
of the best ingredients and attention to detail. Coulson's initial advice
was not strictly for the amateur cook: preparing the breakfast at Sharrow
Bay is not deemed a job for trainee chefs. There is always a head chef at
the stove, a commis to assist and a third on either toast and marmalade duty
 -the kitchen makes 1,500lbs of jam and marmalade a year.
Apart from natural pride in the quality of Cumberland sausage and local
black pudding, Coulson also insists on local grilled bacon, or Danish half
back, croutons fried in bacon fat and a fried apple ring as an essential
accompaniment to bacon and sausage.
But cooking all these ingredients to perfection is, according to Coulson,
only a part of the challenge in serving breakfast. Gauging the mood of your
customers is almost as difficult.
There are those who want to be greeted warmly, engaged in conversation about
the weather and plans for the day and those who want to be merely shown to a
table and left alone until the third cup of black coffee. Separating the
chatty from the grumpy is a sensitive task for the waiting staff.
Today, the great British breakfast may have become something of an
anachronism for several reasons including health ones. But, if it is cooked
well and served promptly, it can still be a great meal, the ideal
preparation for a strenuous day out - and excellent value too. My breakfast
at the Fox &amp; Anchor - bacon, tomatoes, egg, black pudding, sausages, fried
bread (only spoilt by some distinctly unBritish baked beans) cost Pounds
6.50 and was so filling that I happily skipped lunch.
London
The Fox &amp; Anchor, EC1, 071-253 4838; Basil Street Hotel, SW3, 581 3311; Hope
&amp; Sir Loin, EC1, 253 8525; The Connaught, W1, 491 0668; The Dorchester, W1,
629 8888; The River Room at The Savoy, WC2, 836 4343; Cosmo, NW3, 722 1398.
Outside London
Sharrow Bay, Ullswater, Cumbria, 07684-86301; Buckland Manor, Broadway,
Gloucestershire, 0386-852626; Airds Hotel, Port Appin, Scotland, 063173-236.
For the best British bacon, sausage and black pudding: Meat Matters, London
N10, 081-442 0658; Swaddles Green Farm, Somerset, 0460-234387; Richard
Woodall, Cumbria, 0229-717237; Morris's Gold Medal Black Pudding,
Lancashire, 0204-71763.
</TEXT>
