<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Food and Drink: Tastes of paradise: smells of hell - Kieran
Cooke samples a fruit with all the aroma of cleaning-out time at a chicken
shed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hurley dug his way round Britain. One evening in the dim recesses of a
Norwich pub I am sure I saw him strike a match on the palm of his sandpaper
hand.
Hurley and durians belong to each other. The durian is the king of
south-east Asia's fruits. It is big, spiky and ugly. Inside its thick skin
the flesh round the seeds - the edible part of the fruit - tastes like
Camembert with sunstroke.
But it is the smell that distinguishes the durian from any other living
thing - except Hurley.
Hurley, who spent the main part of the day up to his haunches in
water-filled ditches, had terrible problems with his socks. No washing
machine could keep his feet in decent order.
One day Hurley thought he had found the solution to his problems. A local
store advertised indestructible socks - expensive items but guaranteed to
withstand all manner of abuse.
Down went Hurley and bought a pair. He gave them an exhaustive road test,
wearing them for a week, day and night.
On the seventh day holes as big as onions appeared in the heels. Hurley and
I went back to the store. 'Put your eyes on them things,' said Hurley,
slapping the socks, now looking like pieces of malnourished seaweed, on the
counter. 'Indestructible you say. I want my money back.'
Whenever I catch the whiff of a durian that moment returns.
The poor salesgirl gagged. Passing shoppers swooned. Feeling nauseous myself
I persuaded Hurley to accept the offer of a silk tie in exchange for his
faulty indestructibles.
The smell of durians is so pungent that hotels, airlines and bus operators
forbid them. Like cheap perfume in a hot dressing room, the smell can linger
for days. It is the odour of over-ripe compost, it is cleaning-out time at
the chicken sheds.
Yet at the mention of durians the eyes of the average resident of south-east
Asia go wild with desire. Lips salivate. There are groans of ecstasy. There
are few more sensual scenes than a party of young and old sitting around
gorging themselves on durians, faces splattered with the fruit's golden
flesh, seeds licked as clean as marbles.
Hew Choy Sam has a durian orchard in the Malaysian state of Perak. A founder
member of Malaysia's first durian growers association, Hew is a self
confessed durian addict.
'There is something very strange about durians. Just put two of them on a
stall by the road and everyone wants to stop and smell and chat. People are
obsessed with them: they search all their lives for the perfect one.'
There are heated arguments over where the best durians come from. Thailand
is the biggest producer. But Malaysians say the Thais have allowed durian
production to become too commercial. Thai durians keep longer because they
are harvested while still hanging on the tree. Hew says durians must be
allowed to drop. Only then is the flesh guaranteed moist and ripe.
'The Thais are even trying to produce an odourless durian so it can be
exported,' says an indignant Hew. 'You can't take the smell out of durians.
For us it is nearly as important as the taste.'
A terrible vision of eating Hurley's socks comes to mind.
Durians are temperamental fruits which are easily infected by pests and
disease. They also command premium prices - a good, highly pungent durian
full of fleshy seeds can fetch up to MDollars 40 (Pounds 10).
There are durian cowboys who sell dud durians to unsuspecting customers.
Durian rustling is common.
During harvesting season Hew, a sprightly 65-year-old, moves his bed out to
his orchard to guard his crop. 'Through the night I count the thuds as
durians hit the ground. It is a lovely sound.'
Hew and his friends think nothing of driving hundreds of miles in search of
the perfect durian. Fruits are tasted with the same diligence as wines are
sipped at a French auction.
The durian has its own mythology. It aids circulation but increases blood
pressure. It is good for the complexion but causes gout. It must never be
eaten with alcohol. It is an aphrodisiac but also creates chronic wind.
When the durian tree has finished dispensing its smelly pleasures to the
world the wood is used for making clogs.
An ideal present for Hurley.
</TEXT>
<XX>
