<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Cookery: Summer treats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIPPA DAVENPORT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Is it really June? Given the treacherous nature of the weather, wise cooks
will hedge their bets by choosing foods that can be served hot or cold
equally well.
Asparagus, which should be at its best just now, is a prime candidate. It is
quick to cook and can be served straight from the pan, sauced with hot,
melted butter to hearten the chilly. More adventurously, asparagus stalks
can be grilled or roasted and sprinkled with toasted sesame seeds or grated
Parmesan.
If the temperature soars, cool the stalks briefly after cooking and dress
them lightly with a fresh herb vinaigrette instead, or with a parsley and
coriander pesto that has been diluted seriously.
Shrimps and prawns with their summery, seaside connotations are also adept
at beating the weather. Freshly-boiled little brown shrimps are best for
flavour - or is nostalgic memory playing me false?
Easier to track down than fresh shrimps are Baxter's potted variety (to
order direct, tel: 0524-410910). A few tubs stashed in the freezer bring
enormous reassurance. Serve the classic way, with wedges of lemon and lots
of toast.
I also like to spoon a few potted shrimps into the bottom of ramekins for
oeufs en cocottes a la creme; or to stir them into a delicate cream and fish
stock bechamel for a satisfyingly simple shrimp sauce to spoon over fillets
of sole or turbot.
Large cold-water prawns and the tails of Dublin Bay prawns are easier to buy
raw than they were. Like potted shrimps, they are useful to keep in the
freezer. Defrosted, painted with oil and seasoned with sea salt and black
pepper, they take hardly any time to sizzle on a griddle or to stir-fry.
When the shells have turned from blue-grey to pink and the air is tinged
with an agreeable whiff of the sea, add a little chopped garlic, ginger and
spring onions for an oriental finishing touch; or lime and chillies for a
Mexican slant; or a handful of basil or a few seeds of fennel and coriander
for a Mediterranean flavour.
Serve the prawns hot in a nest of noodles or rice, with the pan juices
poured over, or serve them just as they are with plenty of good bread to mop
up the juices.
If the weather plays fair, let the cooked prawns become cold and serve them
on a suitable salad bed with a sesame sauce for dipping; or a spicy tomato
and green coriander salsa; or a bowl of saffron-flavoured mayonnaise.
Uncurling the flesh from the shells is messy but fun, appealing to primitive
picnicker instincts, and sucking the shells at the end is the best part of
all, for the shell is where the sweetest flavour lies. Finger bowls and
large mini tablecloth sized napkins are advisable. Here is a good way to
serve prawns and asparagus in tandem:
ASPARAGUS RICE WITH PRAWNS (serves 6)
I have written this recipe for serving hot. But for hot-weather eating, the
dish can be served cold equally well. In that case, though, I suggest using
olive oil rather than butter to anoint the rice. And instead of Hollandaise
or Bearnaise sauce to partner the dish, I would hand round a bowl of
tarragon-flavoured mayonnaise thinned to the consistency of pouring cream by
beating in yoghurt, fromage frais or soured cream. Another good - and less
rich - sauce is a fresh tomato coulis.
Ingredients:  3/4 lb basmati rice; 1 1/2 lb asparagus; 2 to 3 dozen raw
tails of Dublin Bay prawns; 5 to 6 inches of cucumber; a little butter; a
large pinch of sugar; a splash of tarragon vinegar; 1 or 2 tablespoons of
olive oil; half a lemon.
A 3pt ring mould is needed for this recipe. The rice is moulded in it and
used as a 'vase' to contain a king-size bunch of short lengths of asparagus.
Method: Scrape or peel the asparagus stalks, discarding the woody bases of
the stems. Then cut the stems down to a length suitable for standing upright
in the middle of the ring of rice, and chop the trimmings into pea-size
pieces. These tender trimmings can be used to stud the rice and flavour it
deliciously.
Peel and seed the cucumber. Dice the flesh into pea-size pieces, toss with
the sugar, tarragon vinegar and a pinch of salt and set aside for five
minutes or so.
Drop the cucumber into a large pan of heavily-salted water and boil for a
minute or so. Fish the cucumber out of the pan and pat it dry. Then drop the
diced asparagus trimmings into the same water and cook until just tender.
Remove and pat dry, reserving the cooking liquor.
Let the rice soak in cold salted water while the vegetables are cooking.
Then drain it and boil it in the water in which the cucumber and asparagus
were cooked so that it benefits from the build-up of flavours.
When the rice is just cooked, drain it and refresh it under a cold, running
tap. Drain again, season well, and stir in the chopped and cooked
vegetables. Mix and bind with up to 1oz of cool, melted butter, pack the
mixture into the lightly-buttered ring mould, and cover with buttered foil.
Everything up to this stage can be done well ahead.
To re-heat the rice for serving, stand the mould in a roasting tin
containing enough freshly-boiled water to come halfway up the sides of the
mould, and slip the tin into an oven heated to 375`F/190`C (gas mark 5) for
about 15 minutes until the rice is hot.
Meanwhile, boil or steam the asparagus and prepare the prawns. Season them
with sea salt, pepper and a good squeeze of lemon and toss them in enough
olive oil to make the shells glisten all over. Heat a wok or a large saute
pan thoroughly. Add the prepared prawns and saute or stir-fry, turning them
until the shells are pink and the flesh is hot and cooked right through.
Let the prawns rest in the pan while you un-mould the ring of rice on to a
flat, warmed dish, blot the asparagus dry, and stand it in the ring. Arrange
the prawns all around the rice and pour their pan juices over the rice.
Serve with good bread and the sauce of your choice.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
