<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Food and Drink: Good value fizz - Appetisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANCIS ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Like manufacturing Easter eggs, winemaking is basically a part-time job. A
month of frenetic activity punctuates an otherwise relatively tranquil
existence. Hence flying winemakers who commute between hemispheres to double
their vintage experience, and hence so many winemakers' secret ambitions to
experiment with more demanding wine styles such as fortified and sparkling
wines, writes Jancis Robinson.
It is no surprise, therefore, to come across Maison La Motte, a vivaciously
sparkling version of James Herrick's still Chardonnay from his three
vineyards in the Languedoc, on sale at Pounds 7.99 at Safeway and Victoria
Wine. Given its sparkle in the Loire by the traditional champagne method, it
shows that Limoux does not have the southern French monopoly on good value
fizz.
The Savoie sparkling winemaking business Varichon et Clerc proves the same
point, more clumsily but much more cheaply, with its Sparkling Chardonnay on
sale at Asda for Pounds 4.99. This is also southern French fruit, but given
its sparkle in the Alpine foothills.
Much better buys from Asda, however, come from Limoux but are not Limoux's
most famous product, Blanquette (soon to be Cremant) de Limoux. The
charming, still red Pinot Noir, Vin de Pays 1992 at just Pounds 3.75 is a
steal for a lightly oaked, flattering wine designed to be drunk, not too
warm, this very day.
Also definitively a summer wine is Asda's Blanquette Methode Ancestrale
Pounds 3.99, another true bargain from Limoux. This is the most traditional
form of sparkling wine - despite the EU's insistence that those made by the
champagne method be labelled 'traditional method' - left sweetish and
lightly fizzing with, traditionally, the sediment from the second
fermentation in bottle still lurking in the bottle.
It would be unreasonable to expect a supermarket to live with as
frighteningly natural a thing as sediment, so it has been removed, by
disgorgement a la champenoise, but the wine would make a genuinely
delightful appley aperitif or light pudding wine with something not too
sweet such as strawberries.
English winemakers are also increasingly putting sparkle in their wines,
partly to boost their selling price and partly because the cool summers (and
some soils) of England can be remarkably like those of Champagne. Heritage
English Sparkling from the Thames valley via Safeway and Victoria Wine at
Pounds 7.99 has nice lees-aged aromas, a little bit of bite, and does not
have a great deal of gas.
The process of ageing sparkling wine on its yeast lees to give it that
special character is still far from fully understood, but champagne giants
Moet &amp; Chandon have been working on it. Their most communicative winemaker
Richard Geoffroy was in London this week to divulge the results. Science
backs up our palates in demonstrating that it works best on the classic
Champagne grapes Pinot and Chardonnay, if kept on the lees preferably for at
least five years, and cannot be used to add class to essentially poor wine.
But his real bombshell was the news, after all these years, that champagne
bottles are probably best stored upright rather than horizontal. Champagne
corks are quite different animals, expected to do a quite different job,
from still wine corks, and the less the wine is in contact with them, the
better apparently.
In this new spirit of openness, Moet &amp; Chandon is launching its new
non-vintage Brut Imperial in Britain this month, based on wines from the
superb 1990 crop, with a smart back label spelling out this fact, together
with percentage of reserve wines (17) and the varietal composition of the
blend. Bravo] And the wine itself is a worthy emissary too.
Those looking for a more obscure champagne-with-a-story could do worse than
Gatinois NV, Pounds 181.80 a case or Pounds 16.80 a bottle from Haynes
Hanson &amp; Clark on 071-376 2737. The deputy mayor of Ay sells most of his
grapes to Bollinger but produces wines like this powerfully flavoured, Pinot
Noir-dominated blend with the rest of the produce from his seven hectares of
grand cru vineyards.
J. Sainsbury is doing its bit to drain the European wine lake by launching a
pair of Sicilian wines, on special offer for the next two weeks at Pounds
1.99 (usual price Pounds 2.69). The red is aquiver with acidity and did not
appeal to me as much as the white, a relatively robust, lively blend of
Trebbiano with Italy's most planted grape variety, Catarratto. JR
Wine collectors are spoilt for choice in London next week with sales at
Sotheby's and Christie's. Sotheby's sale on Wednesday includes the cellar
from Boulestin's restaurant. Details and catalogue on 071-408 5051. Jill
James
To clarify last week's item about the private cellar being offered at
Christie's (071-839 9060) in London on Thursday. The 1947 Cheval Blanc,
mentioned as being of special interest, is expected to fetch Pounds 10,000
to Pounds 15,000 per dozen and it is the sale's two super lots which are
estimated at Pounds 200,000 to Pounds 300,000 each. There will be mixed lots
ranging in estimate from as little as Pounds 80.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
