<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Finance and the Family: Think ahead on gilts - What to do as
redemption time nears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DYSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most gilt-edged securities have set redemption dates when the government
pays back investors. This week, for instance, Treasury 10 per cent 1994 was
repaid. In August, Pounds 1.24bn of Exchequer 12.5 per cent 1994 (issued in
1977) will be repaid, followed in November by Pounds 1.9bn of Treasury 9 per
cent 1994 (issued in 1969).
If you have either, you should be thinking already of what to do. You can
either hold them to redemption and seek a new home for the money, or sell in
the market now and re-invest while gilt yields are high and prices
depressed.
If you hold to redemption, you will get the Pounds 100 face value of the
stock with no brokerage costs. But if you sell in the market now, you might
well get slightly more; at mid-week, the bid price (what a seller receives)
was Pounds 101.5.
The extra 1.5 per cent should more than compensate for the fact that selling
through the market means investors have to pay a dealing commission.
The table includes some suggestions of stocks which might be suitable
replacements. All have pros and cons.
Gilts normally offer lower yields, as the payments are guaranteed. The stock
suggested here, Treasury 6 per cent 1999, has a relatively low income yield
but the return is good if held to redemption, with the net yields
particularly attractive. The 8 per cent 2003 is a good all-rounder.
The snag with Eurosterling bonds is that dealings are only in bearer form.
Royal offers a good yield if held to maturity. Alliance &amp; Leicester also has
a good yield but can be traded only in multiples of 10,000. The Fleming bond
is particularly suitable for offshore or gross income-seekers.
Permanent interest-bearing shares (Pibs) have one major drawback: they do
not have a redemption date. So, the only way you can get your money back is
by selling in the market, with no assurance of a good price. The yield on
the Britannia Pibs is good, and deals are possible in multiples of Pounds
1,000. Zero dividend preference shares offer no income as such but are
highly tax-efficient, with a good total return.
TR Technology is well covered with less than four years to run, while the
Fleming zero offers an excellent balance of low risk and reasonable reward -
but, of course, only if you hold it to maturity.
Michael Dyson is a director of BZW Capital Markets.
</TEXT>
