<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Finance and the Family: Down - but not yet out - What next
for C&amp;G and Lloyds?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After euphoria comes disappointment for most Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester
customers, who had been looking forward to generous pay-outs from the
building society's take-over by Lloyds bank.
Lloyds was to have paid C&amp;G Pounds 1.8bn in cash, which the society intended
to distribute among most of its 1.4m customers and staff.
All C&amp;G investing members would have been entitled to a bonus of 10 per cent
of the balance in their accounts once the deal was completed - providing
they had the account at March 31 1994 and held it to completion day. Voting
investors and all borrowers would have been entitled to a Pounds 500 cash
pay-out as well.
The plan was thrown into doubt when Sir Donald Nicholls ruled in the High
Court this week that Lloyds could not make cash payments to members who had
been investors for less than two years before December 31 1993. Investing
members are those with a share account such as Cheltenham Gold, London Share
or Instant 7.
The judgment also suggested that the society's borrowers - around 370,000 of
them - could not be paid at all unless they happened to have a share
account.
C&amp;G had wanted to give generously to its more recent investing members and
to its borrowers to ensure that the deal went through. It needs the
approval, in separate votes, of both types of member but it faces a
potential problem.
Since about 27 per cent of the society's 840,000 voting investors have been
with the society for less than two years, C&amp;G wanted to include them in its
distribution of sweeteners for fear of their scuppering the deal.
Customers of societies taken over by C&amp;G in the past two years - Heart of
England and Mid-Sussex - count as C&amp;G members providing they had been
members of their old societies since December 1991.
So, what should customers of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester do now?
An FT straw poll in a Birmingham branch of C&amp;G after the judgment found many
disgruntled customers. But anger should not be a reason to consider leaving
the society.
There is no suggestion that the High Court has stopped the merger taking
place - simply that it objects to elements of its structure.
Lloyds says its bid still stands and C&amp;G is trying to come up with a new
structure acceptable both to its voting members and to the Building
Societies Commission. The commission's challenge to C&amp;G's original plan led
to the court hearing.
C&amp;G says it will be several weeks before it will be in a position to say
anything substantive. But it still wants to come up with a deal to benefit
all its members and staff and it might yet decide to appeal against the
ruling.
While C&amp;G is not commenting on the form a restructuring might take, analysts
have suggested:
Offering preference shares to all shareholders and borrowers, or offering
these shares to new members. It is unlikely that C&amp;G would be allowed to
offer shares which could be exchanged easily for cash.
Giving members of less than two years' standing some value for the surrender
of their voting rights.
Closing the society to new members until all had acquired at least two
years' standing.
Halting the growth of the society in this way would be a drastic step,
although C&amp;G has barred new customers from joining as it considers its
options.
It says that it will be closed only for a few days to stop people from
joining in the mistaken belief that they will be able to make money by doing
so.
Loans threat, Page VIII
</TEXT>
