<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Finance and the Family: Winners and losers in a falling
market - A look at why some shares have been hit hard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The cold downdraft felt by the stock market since the beginning of February
has turned attention from recovery plays to the more defensive types of
stock which traditionally do well in more difficult times.
Mark Brown, equity strategist at Hoare Govett, says that when the market
started to fall at the beginning of February, there was a classic rotation
of sectors. Those which performed best in the previous 18-month recovery
phase - such as banks and building stocks - were the first to fall in the
shake-out.
At NatWest Securities, Bob Semple says that examining the reasons for the
market's fall - mainly, a fear that inflation was rising again and interest
rates would be increased to control prices - explains the winners and losers
among sectors and stocks.
Bond markets were hit particularly by interest rate worries, so
high-yielding equities such as utilities did badly. That, plus renewed
concerns about regulation for many utilities, explains the poor showing in
the league tables by companies like British Gas and British Telecom, as well
as the water and electricity groups.
Similarly, fears of rising interest rates have hit the building materials
and construction areas, both cyclical sectors which did well when the market
was rising. That explains the presence of stocks like Caradon, Anglian Group
(which warned on profits in March) and George Wimpey.
Conversely, sectors which are seen as benefiting from inflation - whether or
not they do, in fact - have fallen less sharply. That includes
consumer-related sectors such as food retailers and brewers and stocks such
as J. Sainsbury, Tesco and Wm Morrison, and some stores groups.
Warburg Securities suggests that food retailers, which have been
experiencing margin pressure from the various price-cutting campaigns, could
widen their margins again if inflation returns.
Oil has been the best-performing sector since the market peak, but that has
had more to do with a rising oil price, and the bid for Lasmo, than with the
market. Similarly, other commodity prices have been rising, helping the
extractive industries sector and RTZ, in particular.
Banks and financials have been poor performers. Merchant banks were caught
up in the market whirlpool: they make money from a high stock market through
trading securities and acting in bids, rights issues and flotations. Thus,
when the market falls, their shares fall. High in the poor performers' list
are SG Warburg, Hambros and Kleinwort Benson, despite profit growth.
Worst performers in the banking sector among FT-SE 100 stocks have been
Standard Chartered and HSBC. Both were affected by the slide in the Hong
Kong stock market, and the former by concerns that Lloyds Bank would sell
its stake in Standard Chartered after its bid for the Cheltenham &amp;
Gloucester building society. Life insurance groups are still under a cloud
from the row over sales of personal pensions and possible compensation.
Bids (or rumours of them) have been behind some of the strong individual
stock performances. Lasmo and Hogg both received bids, while Portals nearly
did. Meanwhile, companies with well-known problems such as London
International Group and Eurotunnel have seen their shares near the top of
the poor performers' list.
Small companies have, in aggregate, outperformed large ones on the way down,
with the 'small cap' index falling less steeply than the FT-SE 100. This
often happens as fund managers, looking to reduce their exposure to equities
and raise cash, pick the most tradeable stocks where they can deal more
easily.
