<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Finance and the Family: New issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VideoLogic, an electronics company based in Kings Langley, north of London,
is being demerged from its parent Avesco, the quoted broadcast equipment
services group, and will be floated on the stock market through a placing
which will value the company at up to Pounds 83.9m, writes Alan Cane. Some
Pounds 21.5m before expenses is being raised.
The need to demerge the company complicates the issue. Existing Avesco
shareholders will receive one VideoLogic demerger share for each Avesco
share and will have a preferential opportunity to participate in the
placing.
Warburg, which is underwriting the placing, will invite selected brokers and
intermediaries to take up any shortfall.
The share price, being set through a book-building exercise, is expected to
fall between 55p and 70p and applications close at noon on June 30.
VideoLogic is a leader in the design of chips and boards which can be fitted
into personal computers to enable them to display full-motion video,
essential for many multi-media applications.
The demand for its products is expected to be explosive, given the growth of
the personal computer market and accelerating interest in multi-media.
The company is being demerged because its demands for research and
development cash are now beyond Avesco which, in any case, is anxious to
concentrate on its core business.
</TEXT>
