<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Markets: Why property shares are the party poopers - Bottom
Line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After the party, the hangover. Property shares, which produced a glittering
return of 89 per cent last year, are now languishing in the doldrums. In the
last six months, the sector has fallen by an average of 14 per cent,
compared with a 4.5 per cent fall in the market as a whole.
At first sight, the reasons for this lacklustre performance are not obvious.
The reporting season for big quoted companies, which ended this week,
reveals some spectacular results.
Land Securities, the sector's largest company, produced a 34 per cent rise
in net asset value over the year to end-March, as it reaped the benefit of
the remarkable recovery in the property market over the past year. British
Land did even better. On Thursday, it announced a 46 per cent rise in its
net asset value for the year to end-March.
Moreover, most analysts are predicting healthy - albeit more modest - rises
in values this year. For instance, British Land's net asset value is tipped
to rise from Pounds 4.23 to as much as Pounds 5 this year.
Indeed, the weakness of property shares is less due to a serious setback in
the sector than from the excessive expectations that had been built into
prices. At the start of the year, hopes of rapidly rising property values
were reflected in the average 20 per cent premium to net asset values on
which shares traded, according to UBS, brokers. Since then, they have sunk
to an 8 per cent discount to assets.
The waning of investors' enthusiasm for property shares is partly because
investors became jaded by a glut of new property companies coming to the
market. A more important reason, however, is that the direct property
investment market has gone off the boil, as a result of the ailing state of
the bond market. Total returns from property actually fell in May, according
to Richard Ellis, chartered surveyors.
Many commentators think that property share prices will not start to rise
again until there is convincing evidence of rental growth in the property
market. If bond values suffer another battering, there is a chance that
property prices - and the share prices of the quoted companies - will suffer
further falls.
But even if the big picture for property shares is uninspiring, investors
could still do well by careful selection of property shares. In the last six
months, some of the best-performing smaller companies have bucked the trend:
Shares in Burford Holdings, which yesterday bought London's Trocadero
Centre, have risen by 27 per cent in the last six months, while Helical Bar,
a developer, has increased by 31 per cent.
'Some of the smaller companies are providing more excitement and interest
than the bigger companies,' says Robert Kynoch, of NatWest Securities,
brokers. He cites Capital and Regional and Helical Bar as examples of
companies with entrepreneurial flair and an ability to ride the cycle.
'If you are a clever entrepreneur, there are very few markets where you
can't find value,' says Marc Gilbard, of Goldman Sachs. Of the sector's
smaller companies, he favours Helical Bar, Burford, Allied London, Asda
Property Holdings, Capital &amp; Regional and Chelsfield. Of the larger
companies, he opts for those with good quality portfolios, namely Land
Securities, British land and Brixton Estate.
In the view of many City analysts, values are likely to drift through this
summer. But once property rents start rising, the sector could get a new
lease of life. David Tunstall, of Smith New Court, broker, argues that there
is plenty of scope for share prices to grow, since the sector is at a
relatively early stage of a cyclical upswing. 'We are in a cycle that will
last three to four years,' he says.
</TEXT>
