<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Markets: Building society lottery tickets - Serious Money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN O'CONNOR, personal finance editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Personal investors are paranoid. But maybe that is because everybody is
trying to get them. Look at the evidence.
Last week Financial Secretary Stephen Dorrell appeared to be threatening
dividends. This week the High Court scotched Lloyds' plans to hand money out
to thousands of happy Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester savers and borrowers. And now
the Inland Revenue has been caught sending incorrect assessments to half a
million taxpayers.
The people who are baying hardest for blood are the 1.4m C &amp; G members who
have seen large cash sweeteners torn from their grasp.
True, the scheme has been scotched not killed. And Lloyds and C &amp; G have
always made it clear that if their original proposal was challenged they
would fight. But the fresh uncertainty is deeply worrying for members,
particularly the newer savers and borrowers, who fear that they may get
squeezed out.
The best advice for C &amp; G savers is as clear as it is unpalatable. Sit
tight. Closing down an existing account endangers any rights you may have to
any future payouts. It is possible but by no means certain that newer savers
may be excluded from any payout. But if there is a chance of sharing in a
handout, it would seem foolish to abandon an opportunity which cost you
nothing.
If the court ruling holds, and a merger is pushed through, it sounds as if
no borrowers will benefit. For existing borrowers that is just tough: you
presumably took out a C &amp; G mortgage because it was the best available.
And C &amp; G is doing its best to find some other way of rewarding you.
Remortgaging purely because you may not get a handout would be as expensive
as it is pettish.
The far smaller number of people who were considering taking out a C &amp; G
mortgage, purely in order to benefit from the proposed Pounds 500 handout to
all borrowers, new and old, are in a trickier position.
It was always hard to believe that new borrowers could sign up for the
sweeteners. Buying a winning lottery ticket before the draw is one thing.
Buying a winning ticket for the same price after the draw seems too good to
be true.
If you are looking for a new mortgage and you believe in fairies, it is
worth chancing your luck by going to C &amp; G. Otherwise get whichever mortgage
looks best on the normal yardsticks and, if the answer to your search
happens to be C &amp; G, drink a toast to Tinkerbell.
All those people who were scouring the streets in order to deposit money
with the next C &amp; G can also take a breather.
The High Court ruling is effectively saying that longer term 'shareholders'
are entitled to share in any bonanzas; short term 'speculators' are not. And
the dividing line between the sheep and goats is put at two years.
This rulebook may be torn up. But if you are happy with your building
society account on fundamental grounds (ie you are getting a good rate of
interest without unacceptable strings), sticking with your existing society
will also consolidate any sitting tenant rights you already have.
Once the dust clears, other short-term strategies may become sensible. It
now rests with C &amp; G to challenge the High Court or come up with a workable
proposal.
But longer term what is needed is a far clearer framework for building
society members to act within. Creeping demutualisation means that people
are sometimes suddenly bounced into quasi-shareholder status, with
unexpected claims on the society's assets.
But most building society members have no idea whether their society has any
spare assets or whether merger plans which will unlock them are pending. No
wonder, then, that many of them are starting to treat building society
membership as a lottery ticket. The fault is not in them but in the
fuzziness of the system (Page VII).
*****
Stockbrokers often recommend a nice portfolio of blue chips as if they were
Ovaltine. Our snapshot of winners and losers during the recent stockmarket
shakeout (page V) provides a salutary reminder that not all blue chips are
equal.
Between the market's February peak and its recent trough, the FT-SE 100
index fell by almost 17 per cent. But the best individual FT-SE 100 shares
managed to hold their own, while the worst lost over 30 per cent. And that
is over a period of just four months.
Similar comparisons over longer periods show a far wider range of rises and
falls.
There are two seemingly contradictory messages for investors there. First,
if even blue chips can be that skittish, investing in individual shares
should be avoided.
Secondly, if investing in individual shares, even blue chips, can be that
profitable, it is well worth the effort. Both messages are right. If you
have both the knowledge and the time to select individual shares, it can be
more lucrative than investing through unit and investment trusts. But that
is a rather demanding 'if'.
*****
The sad thing about the latest exposure of the Revenue's failings is that
few people will be surprised. Many individual tax inspectors try their best
to be helpful as well as accurate. But some remain both uninformed and
unhelpful. No wonder, most people still see them as 'the enemy'.
</TEXT>
