<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Finance and the Family: Inland Revenue assessment error - At
a Glance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Taxpayers would be well advised to study their assessments closely this year
following a highly critical report released yesterday from the National
Audit Office on the work of the Inland Revenue.
Of the roughly 5m Schedule D (self-employed) and Schedule E
(pay-as-you-earn) taxpayers who currently receive assessments, 3.2m had to
receive at least one revised assessment - in most cases because they had
been asked to pay too much tax.
In the majority of cases, the reasons for the problems were the fault of the
taxpayer: providing wrong information or failing to supply it on time. But
for 500,000 taxpayers, it was the Inland Revenue that was at fault. And
taxpayers or their professional advisers were at least as likely as the
Revenue to notice the error and request adjustments.
In 62 per cent of these cases, the cause was incorrect allowances and
reliefs made by inspectors, and in 22 per cent a failure to use information
already provided. A further 11 per cent was put down to miscalculation of
income and 3 per cent to incorrect deductions.
The Revenue has pledged to tighten checks and improve levels of accuracy, as
well as to publish new quality targets.
