<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / PM under pressure as Tories fear disaster in Euro-poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's position as prime minister was under fire again yesterday as
the Conservative party braced itself for a rout in the European elections.
In the wake of Thursday's five by-election defeats and amid fears that
Conservative representation in the European parliament will be reduced to
single figures, cabinet ministers moved quickly to shore up the prime
minister's position.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, said Mr Major had 'fought a tremendous
campaign', but 'people wanted to give the government a kick up the bottom'.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said the voters would
eventually give the government credit for taking tough decisions and keeping
its nerve.
However, Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor, said the government was 'deeply
unpopular'. He said he was 'not hopeful about Sunday night', when the
European results will be announced.
Rightwing backbenchers were careful not to criticise the prime minister
publicly ahead of the European election results. But Mr Major is expected to
face blunt criticism over the party's poor electoral performance when the
Commons reassembles on Tuesday.
Rightwing MPs said privately there would be demands for a radical
reappraisal of the government's approach to the European Union.
Sir Teddy Taylor, a leading Euro-sceptic, said the party would 'solve
nothing' by replacing Mr Major. But the voters had 'shown in the
astonishingly low turnout for the Euro polls that they are fed up to the
teeth with Brussels rule'.
Conservative officials said they had not given up hope of retaining more
than 10 of the party's 32 seats in the European parliament.
But Mr David Butler, the leading psephologist and fellow of Nuffield
College, Oxford, said the Conservatives would be left with no seats if the
Eastleigh result was replicated in the 84 mainland European parliament
seats.
Both main opposition parties claimed that the Eastleigh by-election, in
Hampshire, established their position as the main challengers to the
Conservatives in the south of England.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, whose Liberal Democrats overturned a 17,000 majority to
take the seat with a majority of 9,239, said the result was 'a devastating
humiliation for the government'.
