<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / The Lex Column: Lloyds/C&amp;G
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The resilience of Lloyds Bank's shares since Wednesday's High Court ruling
on its bid for Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester suggests the market still believes
the deal will eventually go ahead. A similar signal comes from the
performance of C&amp;G's permanent interest bearing shares or PIBs. Their yield
premium over 15-year gilts has barely moved since Wednesday night's ruling.
Yet there is much at stake if the judge's negative verdict is upheld. Under
the deal as proposed, PIB holders stand to benefit not only from the bonus
paid to investors in C&amp;G, but also from the relative improvement in the
status of their investment.
Since building societies have no equity shares in issue, their PIBs, which
are irredeemable, stand pretty much at the bottom of the pecking order in
the event of a liquidation. Once ownership of the society is transferred to
a bank with an equity share capital, the relative ranking improves. Moreover
with interest then being paid gross, as is normal on subordinated debt, the
paper would have new appeal to overseas investors. Such thoughts saw the
yield on C&amp;G's PIBs move 40 basis points closer to that on gilts in the
immediate aftermath of the original announcement.
If the deal were blocked that gain would be reversed. Moreover the
repercussions would be felt elsewhere in the PIBs market where spreads,
particularly on issues by smaller societies, have narrowed in anticipation
of a broader industry restructuring. Doubtless there is money waiting to
snap up UK building societies, including some accumulated by Irish societies
anxious to expand in the UK. But it is unlikely to be spent if Lloyds and
C&amp;G cannot find a way round the judge's ruling.
</TEXT>
