<DATE>940611
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / The Lex Column: Enterprise/Lasmo
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It would be easy to knock Lasmo's assessment that it is worth at least 180p
a share. Though the figure was produced by consultants DeGoyler and
MacNaughton, the key assumptions were provided by Lasmo itself. The
projected crude price of Dollars 17.50 in real terms is on the generous
side, while the discount rate of 10 to 12 per cent looks low. Use more
realistic assumptions and the net asset value comes tumbling down.
But such calculations of Lasmo's absolute value are of little interest to
the company's shareholders. Much more important is the company's relative
value vis-a-vis Enterprise Oil. Following yesterday's statement that it
would not underwrite a cash offer unless a third party entered the bidding,
the battle is increasingly likely to be decided by the relative value of the
two companies' paper. Altering the assumptions on crude prices or discount
rates makes little difference, as the companies' values would move up or
down in tandem.
Most independent analysts estimate Enterprise's net asset value at one and a
half times Lasmo's, which is exactly how Enterprise's current offer values
Lasmo. That, though, gives Lasmo shareholders no incentive to swap their
shares for Enterprise's. The larger company's problem is that it has little
room to improve its offer. It has failed to demonstrate any significant
value to be created from putting the companies together. A paper offer that
appealed to Lasmo shareholders would probably end up harming its own
investors.
</TEXT>
