<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Futures-related programs
boost Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Blue chip stocks were shaken out of the doldrums yesterday despite a softer
tone in bonds, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 20.31 higher at 3,773.45, as
futures-related buy programs sparked the most robust upturn on Wall Street
in nearly a month. But the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 inched
just 0.81 ahead to 458.67.
However, only 222m shares were traded. The lacklustre volume probably
exaggerated the extent of the Dow's advance, which showed signs of flagging
during the afternoon but caught a second wind in the final hour.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite hardly budged, climbing
a scant 0.66 to 441.84. But the Nasdaq composite jumped 5.37 to 734.25, as a
favourable outlook for semiconductor companies allowed computers stocks to
rebound from this week's sell-off.
The strength of the blue chips, after so many flat sessions, was surprising
in view of the morning's inconclusive economic report. The good news was
that producer prices last month dipped 0.1 per cent, with analysts
forecasting a slight gain. The bad news was that the core index, excluding
food and energy, jumped 0.4 per cent, rather stronger than expected.
The mixed signals on inflation disappointed a bond market in search of fresh
direction. As a result Treasury prices drifted moderately lower, and thus
provided little leverage for stocks. Nevertheless, equities showed
surprising strength, though there was no obvious justification for the
enthusiasm. The big gainers were stocks most likely to benefit from a
buoyant economy, a group which has languished over the past month.
Among the cyclicals, Caterpillar climbed Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 105 1/8
and Cummins Engine added Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 41 7/8 . Steel and
aluminium producers were in demand, partly in response to rising industrial
metal prices in the commodity markets, analysts said. Bethlehem Steel was
marked up Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 21 1/8 , Alcoa pushed Dollars 1 3/4
higher to Dollars 73 and Reynolds added Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 48 1/8 .
Energy stocks were in demand as well, with Mobil appreciating Dollars 1 1/8
to Dollars 82 7/8 and Chevron gaining Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 90 7/8 .
The technology sector benefited from a much needed boost from the
Semiconductor Industry Association's May book-to-bill ratio, which compares
shipments to orders. The keenly watched barometer matched expectations of
continued strength and encouraged investors to shop for bargains.
On the Nasdaq, Cyrix bounced back Dollars 1 to Dollars 27 and Novellus put
on Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 33 1/4 . On the Big Board, Compaq was up Dollars
1 at Dollars 35 3/8 and Texas Instruments Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 77 1/4  .
Meanwhile, PepsiCo was near the top of the NYSE's most active list for the
second day running, though yesterday the share price only dipped Dollars
3/8 to Dollars 31 1/8 . The previous session, the company's profits warning
touched off fears of sustained downturn in soft-drink sales.
Canada
Toronto recorded a small gain in relatively light trading. The TSE-300
composite index was up 13.72 points, or 0.33 per cent, to 4,210.51, for a
loss on the week of about 71 points. Winning issues edged losers by 371 to
358.
In another quiet session, trading volume was up slightly to 45.0m shares
from Thursday's 43.46m, while trading value was CDollars 499.5m compared
with CDollars 516m.
Advances were led by the mining group, which gained 1.81 per cent.
Brazil
Sao Paulo closed up three per cent in light trade after prices rallied for
the third day in a row on portfolio-squaring ahead of the options
settlements and optimism ahead of the adoption of a new currency on July 1.
The Bovespa index of the 56 most-active shares ended up 880 at 30,204
points. Turnover was CR414.4bn (Dollars 195.5).
Telebras TEL. SA, Brazil's most popular blue chip, was very volatile in late
trading. The preferred stock closed up 2.2 percent at CR86.50.
</TEXT>
