<PROFILE>_AN-EFLAKAC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940611
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity market responds to good gains
in gilts - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London's equity market moved up strongly yesterday, shrugging off the news
that the Conservative Party had suffered the expected defeats in five
by-elections and ahead of an expected thumping in the European elections.
The latest rise in the FT-SE 100 index, which closed at the day's best level
of 3,055.9, up 27 points on the session left the index up 58.1, or 1.9 per
cent, over the week. The equity market's second-ranked index, the FT-SE Mid
250, settled a more modest 9.2 up at 3,608.5, up 51.2 over the week. Much of
the impetus for the gain on the week came from much better than expected
data on UK manufacturing output released in mid-week.
The main driving force behind the equity market was the good showing by the
gilt-edged market, which was in positive territory all day, despite the poor
showing by the Government in the elections and a lack-lustre performance by
sterling against the D-Mark.
A further boost for the equity market, later in the day was a strong opening
performance by Wall Street in the wake of the US producer price numbers for
May.
Although closing well below the day's best levels the long gilt closed
around  1/4 firmer, having been up over a half-point at mid-session. March
trade data, seen as slightly disappointing by economists, had little impact
on the market.
One of the day's other plus points was the pick up in market activity as the
week drew to a close. Yesterday's turnover of 618.2m shares followed the
683.8m traded on Thursday and was given a substantial boost by a sizeable
bought deal in Royal Bank of Scotland shares, executed by Smith New Court,
the securities house, and a resurgence of trading activity in Lasmo, the
subject of a bid from Enterprise Oil.
Activity in non-FT-SE stocks accounted for 346.3m shares, or 56 per cent of
the day's total.
The session began with the equity market uncertain and down around 7 points
as marketmakers lowered their opening prices to head off any potential
selling from fund managers following the by-election defeats for the Tories.
News that Mr Nick Knight, equity market strategist at Nomura, the
Japanese-owned stockbroker, had lowered his mid-year forecast for the FT-SE
100 index to 2,500 and his end-year number to 3,000, also played a part in
the market's early caution.
The mark down proved only momentary, however, as a firm opening by gilts
triggered good institutional support as the market regained its confidence.
Share prices began to move sharply better towards midday and accelerated
strongly thereafter, eventually closing at the day's high.
The head of marketmaking at one of the leading UK integrated houses
described the days's performance as 'impressive' but emphasised that
sentiment in the equity market, still badly bruised by the recent bond
market sell off, 'will take some time to rebuild'.
The Lasmo defence document, including a higher-than-expected independent net
asset valuation, triggered an early upsurge in Lasmo shares and there was
intense speculation that a third party may be about to enter the arena.
Other oil shares were boosted by US buying.
The much-rumoured bid from Commercial Union for Victoire, the insurance arm
of French financial services group Suez, appeared in the late afternoon but
was too late to have much impact on CU shares.
</TEXT>
