<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Commodities (Week in the Markets): Copper back on gravy
train
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The copper market was back on the gravy train this week. By Tuesday's close
what remained of the previous Wednesday's shake-out at the London Metal
Exchange had been recouped, and after a Dollars 105 leap on Wednesday the
three months delivery price closed yesterday at Dollars 2,384 a tonne,
Dollars 42 below a fresh 21-month high reached in morning trading but still
Dollars 140.50 up overall.
Yesterday's early strength yesterday had been encouraged by the announcement
of a 12,850-tonne fall in LME warehouse stocks, to 366,200. The figure was
later corrected to 371,200 tonnes, but that still represented a 7,850-tonne
cut - the 24th in succession. Subsequent selling was more influenced by the
appearance of strong resistance above the Dollars 2,400-mark and the failure
of the New York market to maintain the uptrend than by disappointment at the
stocks revision, traders said.
Part of the 40 per cent fall in LME copper stocks since they reached a
16-year peak in February had been due to re-location, industry specialists
Bloomsbury Minerals Economics told the Reuter news agency. But copper demand
would exceed production by about 155,000 tonnes in the first half of 1994.
At the moment the aluminium market lacks such clear justification for its
recent strength, which was resumed this week with a Dollars 51.50 rise to
Dollars 1,406.50 a tonne for three months metal. LME stocks remain close to
their all-time record after registering a modest rise yesterday, instead of
the continued fall that many analysts had expected.
Dealers point out, however, that much of the LME stockpile is unavailable to
the market because it is tied up in long-term financing deals.
At the same time the effects of capacity cuts agreed by producers in the US,
the European Community, Canada, Russia, Norway and Australia are begining to
show through. Provisional figures published yesterday by the International
Primary Aluminium Institute indicate that total stocks of aluminium at
western world smelters, excluding finished end-products, totalled 3.645m
tonnes at the end of April 1994, compared with 3.69m in March.
The examples of copper and aluminium have also been encouraging other LME
markets to look on the bright side. Although additions continued to made to
the exchange's historically-high zinc stockpile, that metal managed an
Dollars 11 rise this week to Dollars 991.50 a tonne for three months
delivery. Meanwhile, in anticipation of stock-building by car battery makers
ahead of the northern hemisphere winter, traders pushed the three months
lead price up Dollars 18.75 to Dollars 540.25 a tonne.
At the London Commodity Exchange the robusta coffee market had another week
of sound and fury, but this time signifying very little. As investment fund
money ebbed and flowed in a basically thin market the September delivery
futures price fluctuated between Dollars 1,985 and Dollars 2,183 a tonne,
before ending Dollars 54 up on balance at Dollars 2,145.
'Many people are just standing aside because of the volatility,' one trader
told Reuter.
At the cocoa market, meanwhile, the September price dipped back below Pounds
1,000 a tonne in lacklustre trading. As the price surrendered Pounds 39 of
its recent rally to end at Pounds 995 a tonne, one dealer commented: 'It
will be hard for cocoa to pick up and it will probably move sideways for a
while. . . Even if it does pick up, there will be origin selling coming in
to put a lid on the market'.
