<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / International Company News: Ziff family's publishing group
put up for sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ziff Communications, the world's largest publisher of computer magazines and
a growing participant in the market for electronic information services, has
been put up for sale by the Ziff family.
The privately-held group, which has annual revenues of approximately Dollars
1bn and employs more than 4,300 people, could sell for between Dollars 2bn
and Dollars 3bn, analysts said.
'We don't know what the price will be, but it appears that there will be a
great deal of interest,' said Mr Steven Rattner of Lazard Freres, which has
been engaged to find a buyer.
Telecommunications companies as well as publishing and media companies
interested in the emerging market for electronic information services are
expected to be attracted by Ziff, analysts said.
Ziff Communications includes Ziff-Davis Publishing, publisher of PC Magazine
which has a paid circulation of more than one million. It is the largest
business magazine of any kind and ranks ninth among US magazines in terms of
advertising revenue.
The company also publishes several other magazines, trade newspapers,
newsletters and books relating to the computer industry and runs several
industry trade events and conferences.
The group also includes ZiffNet, an on-line information service about
computers, and Interchange, an electronic publishing venture due to be
launched commercially later this year. Interchange will carry The Washington
Post's new on-line service and electronic versions of several other
publications.
Mr William Ziff Jr, son of the founder of the family business, retired last
year after running the business for 38 years. His three sons, Dirk, Robert
and Daniel Ziff, and related trusts own approximately 90 per cent of the
business, with the remainder held by other family members.
'Publishing has been at the centre of our family's business interests for
two generations,' said Mr Dirk Ziff, co-chairman of Ziff Brothers
Investments.
'But since our father's retirement last fall, Robert and I have realised
that the company is not where we want to spend our careers. After consulting
with our brother Daniel and our father, it was clear that we should focus
where our skills and interests lie, in the investment field.'
Mr Rattner said that the Ziff family wanted to compete the sale with as few
transactions as possible. 'If it can be sold to a single buyer without
sacrificing proceeds - that would be a priority.'
The Ziff brothers said that the company would not be sold 'to just anybody,'
adding that they would not welcome bids from the company's main competitors,
International Data Group and CMP Publications.
K-III Communications, which owns about 50 consumer and trade magazines, said
it was interested in buying some of Ziff's businesses.
</TEXT>
