FT  11 JUN 94 / International Company News: Norwegian shipowner tumbles to
NKr54m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bergesen, Norway's largest shipowner, yesterday reported a steep fall in
pre-tax profits for the first four months, to NKr54m (Dollars 7.5m) from
NKr212m in the same period last year, reflecting weaker markets for tankers
and LPG carriers.
The company was uncertain about the outlook for the rest of the year. 'No
significant change is expected in the tanker market this summer. If break-up
(scrapping) activity continues, there could be an improvement in the
autumn,' it said.
Group operating revenue fell by NKr81m to NKr865m. Operating profit, before
depreciation costs, was reduced by NKr83m to NKr182m.
Taking depreciation costs of NKr212m into account, against NKr191m, Bergesen
fell to a loss of NKr30m at the net operating level, from a profit of
NKr74m.
The result was bolstered by foreign-exchange income of NKr124m against
NKr91m last year.
Tankers suffered an increase in operating losses, to NKr104m from NKr69m,
while LPG carriers saw operating profits cut by more than half to NKr51m
from NKr121.
</TEXT>
