<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / UK Company News: C&amp;G rules out early statement over court's
ban on Pounds 1.8bn bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society yesterday ruled out making any
announcement for 'several weeks' on its response to a High Court ruling on
Wed-nesday barring the terms of Lloyds Bank's Pounds 1.8bn bid.
The statement appeared to contradict signals from Lloyds that it would like
to be able to say something concrete by the end of next week.
Bankers said Lloyds was confident that it would be able to come up with a
proposal that both satisfied the court and would be true to the spirit of
the original cash offer to the society's members.
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester ruled out suggestions that it would consider issuing
preference shares to customers in lieu of a cash payment.
However, it refused to speculate on alternative ways of getting around the
judgment, such as providing a payment to customers who agreed to transfer
their savings to non-voting deposit accounts.
In a letter sent to its 1.4m customers yesterday, the society advised that
no-one should close any of their mortgage or investment accounts for fear of
jeopardising a potential payment under a revised offer.
It expressed 'great disappointment' in the judgment and said the ruling came
in spite of 'strong legal advice' that the offer was permitted under the act
from two QCs - Mr Jonathan Sumption and Mr Richard Sykes.
The society stressed that its delay at least into July of an announcement on
any revisions to the Lloyds offer was unrelated to its short-term decision
to prevent any new customers from opening accounts.
Building society lottery tickets, Weekend Page II
Down - but not yet out, Weekend Page VII
