<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Riva tumbles into Pounds 2.2m deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REG VAUGHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Following the warning in January of a substantial loss for 1993, Riva Group,
the USM-traded Lancashire-based supplier of electronic point of sale
systems, yesterday announced a pre-tax deficit of Pounds 2.2m, writes Reg
Vaughan.
Mr Peter Giles, chairman, said the loss - which compares with a profit of
Pounds 134,000 - reflected significant trading losses in Spain, Denmark and
France. In view of these the balance sheet was significantly depleted.
The chairman said that trading in continental Europe had been hit by the
continuing recession. However, the UK operations remained profitable. Group
turnover declined from Pounds 59.4m to Pounds 54m.
The chairman said that liquidity remained healthy and although gearing was
high, with the continued support of the banks, the depleted balance sheet
was not expected to affect operations this year.
As losses continued in continental Europe in the first half of the current
year, Mr Giles said he expected 1994 'to be a year of rationalisation and
consolidation.'
In the UK the year had started in line with expectations, with turnover
stable and costs generally under control, but with margin pressure on
hardware sales, Mr Giles said.
Borrowing costs fell to Pounds 695,000 (Pounds 879,000). Losses per share
were 8.6p (0.2p earnings) and there is again no dividend.
</TEXT>
