<PROFILE>_AN-EFLAKAB1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940611
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Homo stingius on the town: Central bankers are at the peak
of their power. But can they stay there
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This has been a banner week for anthropologists. They have been able to
observe a singular concentration and migration of one of mankind's more
influential subspecies: the central bank governor.
The Bank of England's 300th birthday celebrations brought a record 110
serving governors to London for a gala concert on Wednesday and a special
symposium on central banking the following day.
This weekend, the extended posse of central bankers (the Bank is open to
suggestions for a more appropriate collective noun) moves to Basle for
Monday's annual meeting of the Bank for International Settlements in Basle.
If the spotlight is on top central bankers, it is for a good reason. These
guardians of the world's monetary and financial systems have more influence
than for a generation.
This new-found clout will not be immediately apparent this weekend. The
Basle gathering, one of the great annual events of the central banking
world, has echoes of a calmer, bygone age. For once, serious work is put to
one side. Bank governors and their officials, often with spouses in
attendance, glide bonhomously from lunch to cocktails to dinner, perhaps
exchanging the odd word on the need for fiscal austerity and financial
prudence. Many will find that their biggest problem is coping with the
compulsory second helpings so liberally served in the ho-tels clustered
around Basle's main railway station.
On show will be the old clubby, male- dominated world of central banking.
Only Austria, Finland and Poland have women central bank governors. The
guardians of the world's monetary and financial systems are a quietly
spoken, sober-suited bunch, aged mainly between between 50 and 70. They are
gossipy among themselves but cultivate a (frequently false) aura of
discretion towards outsiders.
Contrary to appearances, central bank governors come from varied
professional backgrounds. Until 1990, Mr Hans Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank
president, was a senior Bonn government official who in his youth had
aspired to be a priest. Mr Wim Duisenberg, head of the Netherlands national
bank, is a former socialist finance minister. Mr Donald Brash, the
innovative head of the New Zealand central bank, was once managing director
of the New Zealand Kiwifruit Authority. Others, notably Mr Eddie George of
the Bank of England and Mr Yashusi Mieno, governor of the Bank of Japan,
have been central bankers all their working lives.
They head institutions with very different customs and histories. But once
in harness, they seem to become remarkably like-minded people who are often
more in tune with each other than the politicians and officials of their
national treasuries.
Top central bankers work together closely, meeting every month in Basle.
They are in frequent telephone contact. The 'phone lines between the leading
central banks were humming furiously in February when the bloodbath on the
world bond markets seemed at one moment to threaten the world financial
system.
Although unelected and often paid more than politicians, these many men and
few women are currently going from strength to strength. Their prestige is
unscathed by the existence of 35m unemployed in the industrialised world.
The British government, when faced with the problem of restoring credibility
to economic policy after sterling's unceremonious exit from the European
exchange rate mechanism, found the answer in greater openness, and giving
greater responsibility for monetary policy to the Bank of England. Italy, at
the height of its political crisis, turned to Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the
Italian central bank governor, to be prime minister.
The increasing complexity of financial markets, characterised by a huge
increase in cross-border capital flows and the increased use of arcane
financial instruments, has put a premium on central bankers' expertise.
The acceptance of the idea that inflation is bad for economic growth and
prosperity and that central banks are primarily responsible for combating it
has helped turn central bank governors into public figures. Mr Tietmeyer
spends much of his life lecturing his countrymen and financial markets on
the Bundesbank's determination to control inflation. Britain's Mr George has
been far more visible than his predecessor, following the government's
decision to involve the Bank more in monetary policy.
The independent Bundesbank's success in combating inflation has prompted
other countries as far afield as New Zealand, Chile, Mexico and France to
give their central banks more independence. Demands for independence or
greater autonomy for other central banks, including the Bank of England,
have grown. But, with the possible exception of the Bundesbank, more
autonomy will invariably mean greater accountability.
Today's central bankers must increasingly come to terms with a world in
which they can no longer operate out of the public eye. Mr George, while
welcoming the recent decision to publish the minutes of his monthly meetings
with the chancellor after about six weeks, observed that his new position
was 'not particularly comfortable'.
He meant that, in future, people would be able to judge whether the Bank's
advice to the government had been good or bad. He and his colleagues
currently stand on the crest of a wave of approbation. But central bank
governors are too realistic to believe this will always be the case. As
their mystique is gradually stripped away, they will doubtless have to
justify themselves and their actions far more in the face of growing
critical scrutiny.
</TEXT>
