FT  11 JUN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Tonga the featherweight in the
central banking stakes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ADRIAN P HEWITT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The Central Bank of the Solomon Islands may be a tiddler, as you report
(Observer, June 9), but last month I paid a visit both there and to Tonga's
central bank to assist with manpower development. I conclude that the
National Reserve Bank of Tonga is considerably smaller.
Whether you apply the yardstick used by Central Banking magazine staff
numbers (NRBT 21, CBSI 61) or compare gross national product (Tonga Dollars
110m, Solomon Islands Dollars 186m) or population covered (Tonga 100,000,
Solomons 320,000), the powerhouse of the Pa'Anga comes out a good deal
smaller.
However, the Central Bank of the Solomon Islands has the best display of
shell and feather currency. That's perhaps central banking at its most
basic.
