<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Leading Article: Voteless recovery
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Scare stories of a 'jobless recovery' in the US were just that, merely a
scare. US secretary of labour, Robert Reich, visiting the UK this week, even
boasted that 'in the 16 months the Clinton administration has been in
Washington, the American economy has added more than 3m new jobs in private
industry'. Such have been the benefits of winning an election at an ideal
point in the economic cycle. But this does not necessarily bring political
rewards, as the British prime minister must now know. He gained re-election
precisely when the British recession hit bottom. But for the Conservatives,
this has been a voteless recovery.
Just how voteless was demonstrated by the by-elections on Thursday. In
Eastleigh, for example, a Conservative majority of 17,702 over the Liberal
Democrats at the 1992 general election was turned into a Liberal Democrat
majority of 9,239 over Labour, with the Conservatives in third place. The
European parliamentary election results, due late tomorrow night, may reveal
a massacre. Mr Major must count himself fortunate that the Labour party is
just starting a leadership campaign of its own.
A question that must plague the government is whether the recovery will ever
give it the political benefits it longs for. It has not done so yet, even
though it is well-established. The turn-around in the level of gross
domestic product occurred between the first and second quarters of 1992,
with GDP growth amounting to 1.4 per cent in the year to the first quarter
of 1993, followed by another 2.6 per cent in the year to the first quarter
of 1994.
The most important economic data out this week, those for industrial output
in April, confirm this picture of an increasingly strong recovery,
notwithstanding the tax increases that came into effect subsequent to last
November's budget and in April. Total seasonally adjusted output in the
three months to April was up 1 per cent on the previous three months, with
manufactured output up 1.2 per cent.
Hedged endorsement
This week, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development added
its mite, by providing a carefully hedged endorsement of central planks of
Conservative policy towards the labour market, and by raising its forecasts
for economic growth. The secretariat now expects the economies of OECD
member countries to grow by 2.6 per cent this year (up half a percentage
point on last December's forecast), followed by 2.9 per cent next year.
Buoyancy in its principal trading partners is important for the next leg of
the UK recovery, particularly since yesterday's trade figures confirmed the
disappointingly modest growth in UK exports, notwithstanding sterling's
devaluation after its ejection from the ERM. With Germany forecast by the
OECD to achieve 1.8 per cent growth this year and 2.6 per cent next, the
British export cause should certainly receive a boost.
The OECD's forecast for UK economic growth itself remains around 2.9 per
cent this year and next, which looks plausible. But the problem even with
2.9 per cent economic growth is that it means modest increases in real
disposable incomes after tax, because of the substantial phased tax
increases announced by Mr Norman Lamont and Mr Kenneth Clarke. It also means
the economy would merely be bumping along the bottom of its longer-term
growth trend.
Especially dissatisfied
A simple way to derive that trend is to take annual rates of growth between
successive cyclical peaks and troughs, defined by whether quarterly growth
is turning decisively below trend (in the case of peaks) or above it (in the
case of troughs). The trend growth rate over the last cycle turns out to be
2 1/4 per cent a year - and 2.9 per cent is only modestly better than that.
If voters believe economic growth at the trend rate is their right, as seems
plausible, they are unlikely to find anything special about this
performance.
They will be especially dissatisfied after a fierce recession. If output had
continued to rise on trend from its peak at the end of 1988, it would be 10
per cent higher than it is now. Continuation of economic growth at 2.9 per
cent would not bring the economy back to even half-way between its
peak-to-peak and trough-to-trough trend lines before the end of the
millennium. Yet bringing the economy back to the mid-point still faster
would be risky, since inflationary pressure is not just related to the
amount of slack in an economy, but also to the speed with which it is
eliminated.
The government hopes that economic recovery will somehow offset the many
other reasons for its unpopularity. Yet on present trends, growth may not be
fast enough to make that much of a political difference. At the same time,
forcing the economy to grow still faster than 3 per cent a year, however
tempting, would be irresponsible. The good news for the government is that
the recovery is indeed continuing. The bad news is that it could remain
voteless.
</TEXT>
