<DATE>940611
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Devastated Tories fear an even heavier blow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservatives were devastated yesterday by the party's by-election
defeats, and fearful of an even heavier blow when the European election
results are declared tomorrow night.
Cabinet ministers tried to put a brave face on the party's third-place
results in Eastleigh, Bradford South and Barking, and its second-place
performance in Dagenham and Newham North East.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said he was 'extremely
optimistic' that the Conservatives would recover from the 'short-term blip'
in the party's electoral fortunes to win the next general election.
Conservatives MPs drew comfort from the low turnout in all five polls, which
was interpreted as a sign that core supporters had abstained rather than
switching support to opposition parties.
Mr David Willetts, Conservative MP for Havant, said: 'We have to win back
our supporters, but winning them back from abstention is an easier task than
winning them back from voting for another party.'
But few Tories expect anything other than a crushing defeat in the European
elections. At worst, experts say they could be left without a single seat in
the parliament.
Mr David Butler, the psephologist, said the safest Conservative seat -
Buckinghamshire and East Oxfordshire - would fall to the Liberal Democrats
by a 7 per cent margin if the Eastleigh result were repeated in the 84
British mainland seats.
Such a result would give the Liberal Democrats between 12 and 14 seats,
compared with none in the last parliament; Labour 68 to 70 seats, compared
with 45; and the Scottish National party two seats, up from one. In a
general election, the 21 per cent swing at Eastleigh would reduce the
Conservatives to a handful of seats.
Labour and Liberal Democrat MPs were buoyed by the by-election results, but
strategists disagreed sharply about which party was the principal challenger
to the Tories in the south of England. Mr Jack Straw, Labour's campaign
manager, said its second-place position in Eastleigh showed that confidence
in the Tory party had collapsed.
'By forcing the Conservatives into third place, and achieving a significant
improvement in our share of the vote, it was Labour in Eastleigh that
inflicted the truly devastating blow to John Major and his government,' he
said.
'There has not been a result like Eastleigh, where the Tories have gone from
a strong first to a poor third place, in modern British politics.'
However, the Liberal Democrats pointed to a fall of about 500 votes in
Labour's total vote since the 1992 general election as evidence that Labour
had failed to win over Conservative supporters.
Mr Matthew Taylor, Liberal Democrat campaign organiser, said Labour's vote
had fallen 'despite the biggest effort by Labour in a by-election for many
years'. He added: 'Where the Labour party tries to attract new voters, they
fail and we succeed.
'The hardest elections of all for Liberal Democrats to win are the European
elections. We have not done it before. We believe we now have. We are in a
buoyant mood,' he said.
'If the government does not learn the lessons of these elections, they are
going to face further humiliations, culminating in their defeat at the
general election.'
In the Liberal Democrats' first official forecast of the European campaign,
Mr Charles Kennedy, president, said the party was certain to win its first
seats: 'We should win two or three for sure.'
William Hill, the bookmaker, shortened its odds on a Labour victory at the
next general election from 4-6 to 4-7, with the Tories lengthening from
11-10 to 5-4 and the Liberal Democrats at 25-1.
</TEXT>
