<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Marchioness group wins inquest battle
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Families of the 51 people who died in the 1989 Marchioness riverboat
disaster on the Thames yesterday won the right to seek to have the inquests
into the deaths reopened before a new coroner.
The Court of Appeal said that Dr Paul Knapman, the coroner who conducted the
original inquests, had shown 'apparent bias' in describing Mrs Margaret
Lockwood-Croft, the mother of one of the victims, to a newspaper as
'unhinged'.
Lord Justice Simon Brown said it was possible that Dr Knapman thought the
families were troublemakers and unfairly undervalued their argument for
resumed inquests. Lawyers for Dr Knapman said they were considering asking
the House of Lords for leave to appeal against the ruling.
