<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Honda to spend extra Pounds 330m at Swindon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Honda is to invest a further Pounds 330m in its car production facilities at
Swindon, Wiltshire, to raise capacity by 50 per cent to 150,000 cars a year
by 1998. It will also consider a second expansion programme for the plant at
the end of the decade.
This increase in production will almost double the value of Honda's
components purchases in Europe to nearly Pounds 1bn a year.
It will also create another 500 jobs at the plant in addition to substantial
extra employment projected for the company's 211 UK and Continental
suppliers.
The plant currently employs 1,400 people, a figure due to rise to 2,000 next
year when production is scheduled to reach 100,000 units. This compares with
32,139 in 1993 and 50,000 scheduled for this year.
Mr Kazue Ito, who is to take over as president of Honda Motor Europe at the
end of this month, said yesterday that the value of components purchases
would increase by proportionately more than car-unit production. This was
mainly because Honda intended to increase 'local' - UK and continental
European - content from the current 80 per cent to between 85 per cent and
90 per cent.
Cars to be produced at Swindon - notably a successor to the Honda Concerto -
will also be more sophisticated and require a higher absolute level of
components.
Mr Nobuhiko Kawamoto, Honda president, who yesterday announced the increased
capacity plans, left the door open to further collaboration with other
manufacturers in Europe, including both Rover and Rover's parent, BMW.
The Swindon plant is also to start exports to the Middle East and Africa as
part of an overall restructuring of Honda's European operations in the wake
of BMW's takeover of Rover. These exports could reach 10,000 a year by 1999,
Mr Ito said. Honda sells 50,000 cars a year in the two regions, almost
wholly imported from Japan - many in kit form. Other countries may take
Swindon exports, he indicated.
Honda also said yesterday that it has set a total annual target for European
car sales of at least 300,000 by the year 2000 - a 2 per cent market share
compared with the market share of 1.4 per cent Honda presently has. Half of
these vehicles would be supplied from Swindon.
Meeting all these demands would exceed even the expanded Swindon capacity,
Mr Ito acknowledged.
The investment programme includes Pounds 30m for a steel body-parts
pressings plant at the Swindon site, which will end Honda's dependence on
Rover for body pressings for both the Swindon-built Honda Accord and a new
medium-size car, code-named HH, which is to enter production at Swindon this
autumn.
This car - to be called the Civic like Honda's existing medium-size range -
will be produced at a rate of up to 100,000 units a year when it goes on
sale next spring. Rover's version of the HH, code-named Theta and replacing
the current 200/400 series, also goes on sale next spring under continuing
collaboration agreements between the two companies signed last month.
</TEXT>
