<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Party keen to make sure all candidates look like leaders:
Runners in the Labour leadership race start to declare
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The gun has fired for the start of Labour's leadership campaign, but the
rules under which the contest will be fought are still not clear. Labour's
procedure committee, chaired by Mr David Blunkett, the party chairman, will
not set out final guidelines until after nominations close on Thursday.
As a result, there is uncertainty about the extent to which the candidates
will be able to draw on Labour's publicity machine.
Party managers believe that Labour's lead in the opinion polls and its
strong performance in Thursday's by-elections reflects, in part, the
unofficial campaign waged since John Smith's death.
They are keen to make sure that all the candidates look like leaders -
especially on television. But the procedure committee has yet to decide how
far Labour's highly effective communications department should be involved
in leadership events.
The most likely approach is that the party's publicity machine will be told
to restrict itself to the technical role of assisting candidates to set up
meetings and interviews.
The issue is complicated by the department's continuing responsibility to
help publicise the candidates' shadow-cabinet responsibilities.
This means, for example, that it will continue to brief the media on Home
Office affairs for Mr Tony Blair, and on employment matters for Mr John
Prescott. It is not clear how the department will distinguish between the
party role and the leadership aspirations of Mrs Margaret Beckett, the
acting party leader.
The three main candidates are expected to give a series of high-profile
interviews over the weekend, , and all are expected to address the annual
conference of the GMB general union in Blackpool on Monday night, and the
TGWU general union in London on Thursday.
Mr Denzil Davies, former shadow defence secretary, could be a fourth
surprise candidate, although his ability to attract the 34 nominations he
needs remains in doubt.
Mr Robin Cook, who had seemed a strong candidate, said yesterday that he
would not stand. Without indicating who he would support in the contest, the
shadow trade and industry secretary said: 'I believe it is vital for the
health of the party that there should be a contest, and it is now clear that
there will be a contest. In those circumstances I do not intend to stand
myself.'
</TEXT>
