<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Beckett says she offers continuity and stability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Margaret Beckett yesterday claimed credit for Labour's decision to 'try
to drive' the Tories into third place in this week's Eastleigh by-election,
as she announced her intention to enter the contest to succeed John Smith as
Labour leader.
The MP for Derby South also made clear that she would enter the race for
deputy leader - a post to which she was first elected some two years ago.
She said that by declaring a vacancy from next month for the deputy leader's
post, she was ensuring that all candidates could enter the contest 'on equal
terms'.
Mrs Beckett was in confident mood after the widespread praise for her
performance as acting leader before this week's European elections and
parliamentary by-elections. She emphasised her experience and said she could
offer 'continuity and stability'.
'People don't have to guess what kind of leader I can be - they can see,'
she said. 'I believe I have the measure of John Major and I believe I would
have the measure of any of his successors.'
Asking party members to judge her on her 'ability to manage and unify' the
party and to 'communicate its ideals', Mrs Beckett sought to highlight her
expected appeal to female voters - 'whose votes Labour needs to win'.
Underlining the central role she has played in Labour's recent campaigns,
Mrs Beckett said it was her decision to try to push the Conservatives into
third place in this week's Eastleigh by-election - a result the party
achieved by a margin of some 1,500 votes.
'I have led our campaigning through two successful local election campaigns,
including the key London elections this year, a number of by-elections and
this year's Euro-elections,' she said. 'In all of these campaigns I have
played the key role behind the scenes as well as taking a full part on
stage.'
Women are likely to feature prominently among Mrs Beckett's key backers at
Westminster, although it remained unclear last night who would be running
her campaign. She appeared unaccompanied at yesterday's crowded press
conference, saying she was still 'in the very early stages of my campaign'.
Mrs Beckett, 51, may also get support from Labour's hard-left because of her
radical and fervently Euro-sceptic past.
Her vitriolic attack 13 years ago on Mr Neil Kinnock, the former Labour
leader, for his failure to back Mr Tony Benn, then running for deputy
leader, is still remembered.
But she has since built up a reputation as a tough-minded and unflappable
pragmatist, first as shadow chief secretary to the Treasury, where she
policed the spending instincts of her colleagues, and more recently as
deputy leader.
There was certainly no evidence of any hankering to return to her leftwing
roots yesterday, although she did make an early attempt to outflank Mr John
Prescott, one of her leadership rivals, on the issue of full employment that
he is putting at the heart of his campaign. Mrs Beckett said that as well as
aiming for 'the greatest possible level of employment', Labour should seek
new ways of enhancing workers' job security.
She said she did not believe that the implications for 'the financial
structure of this country' of the growth in performance pay and short-term
contracts had been properly thought through.
Mrs Beckett called on all candidates for the leadership to run for the
deputy leadership as well. She even said Mr Blair's name had been mentioned
in connection with the deputy leadership 'on a previous occasion'.
</TEXT>
