<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Speculation mounts over editor of Independent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior journalists at The Independent believe that its main founder Mr
Andreas Whittam Smith may soon decide to step down as editor.
Staff believe he may have privately taken the decision in the past week,
although nothing formal has been said and fellow directors of Newspaper
Publishing, the company that publishes The Independent, have not been
informed of any imminent change.
The intense speculation follows the motion of no confidence in Mr Whittam
Smith passed by journalists at the paper, and clear signs that the main
shareholders - El Pas of Spain and La Repubblica of Italy - have begun an
informal process of trying to find a new editor.
The uncertainty over Mr Whittam Smith comes as the latest official
circulation figures show a modest respite for both The Independent and The
Independent on Sunday.
Daily sales in May were 276,660, up from 271,372 in April, but for the six
months from the beginning of December to the end of May the drop was 18 per
cent compared with the same period last year. The Sunday paper sold 324,711
in May, up from 317,720 in April but down 13.7 per cent over the six-month
period.
The possible bottoming out of the circulation came as The Times recorded
sales of 517,575, a 42 per cent rise year-on-year and the highest
circulation in the paper's history.
The Daily Telegraph, which in April fell below 1m sales for the first time
for more than 40 years, dropped further in May. Sales averaged 993,395
compared with 998,921 in April and a December-to-May figure of 1.04m. The
Guardian, which fell to 397,172 in April, rose to 401,831 in May. The
Financial Times rose to 300,135 in May compared with 298,971 in April.
</TEXT>
