<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / BBC dispute returns to Acas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Talks between the BBC and its main broadcasting unions will resume at Acas,
the conciliation service, on Monday in a further attempt to resolve the
dispute that has already led to two 24-hour strikes.
The BBC offer to return to Acas to clarify its final package came after
Bectu, the main technical union, and the National Union of Journalists
decided to call off industrial action planned for tomorrow, the day of the
European election results.
Unions were also encouraged by the willingness of the BBC management to
discuss the detail of the terms of employment - a key factor behind the
dispute.
As a result of the signs of flexibility further industrial action planned
for Tuesday has also been dropped although the unions have given no
commitment beyond then.
The dispute is about the implementation of performance pay and some terms
and conditions of employment which can in future be subject to negotiation
in individual BBC directorates rather than centrally.
Movement came yesterday after a letter to staff from Mr John Birt, the
director-general, saying that the BBC needed a closer link between pay and
individual performance. Mr Birt said: 'Annual increments - raising pay
automatically because someone remains in the job - are antiquated and have
no place in a modern workplace.'
He warned, however, that if there were any further industrial action the BBC
would invoke formal procedures which would almost certainly lead to
suspension of striking staff.
A continuing series of strikes could not come at a more potentially
embarrassing moment for the BBC.
The government is in the final stages of completing a white paper on the
future of the corporation which is due to be published this month or next.
It would be difficult for the BBC management to decide that a 'final offer'
was not final after all.
The return to Acas also helps union leaders who do not want to be seen to be
responding to threats of suspension.
</TEXT>
