<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / US judge orders Microsoft recall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US federal judge has ordered Microsoft to recall versions of its personal
computer operating system MS-DOS that contain data compression technology
found by the court to have violated patents held by Stac Electronics, a
small Californian software company.
MS-DOS is used by millions of PC users. The worldwide recall covers
offending ver sions of the MS-DOS operating system software, and computers
containing the software, that are currently in computer stores. Copies of
the Microsoft program already in use by PC buyers are not affected by the
recall.
The judge also issued a permanent injunction ordering Microsoft to stop
making, using and selling MS-DOS 6.0 and 6.2 versions of the software that
contain a feature called 'DoubleSpace' that doubles the amount of data that
can be stored on a PC hard disk.
The injunction follows a February jury decision that Micro soft's
DoubleSpace technology infringes two patents owned by Stac Electronics.
Microsoft was also ordered to pay Stac Dollars 120m in compensatory damages.
Microsoft has said that it will appeal against the verdict and said
yesterday it would also ask the Federal Appellate Court to stay the
injunction and recall the order.
Microsoft has already shipped a new version of MS-DOS with the offending
features expunged, to 1500 PC manufacturers.
The company was unable to estimate the volume of products that could be
affected by the recall.
Industry analysts said, however, that the recall could cause significant
disruption in the PC market if thousands of computers are pulled off
dealers' shelves worldwide.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Microsoft Corp.
    Stac Electronics Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
