<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / North Korean nuclear crisis deepens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALEXANDER NICOLL and MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The crisis over North Korea's nuclear capabilities deepened yesterday as the
US said it was increasing its intelligence efforts to prepare for the
possible use of nuclear weapons by Pyongyang.
President Clinton met with senior defence and foreign policy advisers at the
White House and made it clear in talks by telephone with his South Korean
counterpart, Kim Young-sam, that the US was seeking punitive United Nations
sanctions against the North for its suspected nuclear programme. A draft UN
resolution is expected to be drawn up next week.
Mr Ashton Carter, US assistant secretary of defence, said North Korea had
ballistic missiles and 'they may have other things as well.' The US has said
that North Korea is believed to have as many as two nuclear weapons and is
developing more. He said the US would quickly send more warplanes, ships and
troops to the tense peninsula in the event of trouble.
Even more sharply, assistant Secretary of State Robert Gallucci said in an
appearance before a convention on nuclear arms control that President
Clinton had made clear if a nuclear weapon were used by North Korea 'that
would be the end of the North Korean state.'
In Vienna, North Korea said it could no longer guarantee continuity of
nuclear safeguards and would ask two United Nations inspectors to leave the
country. 'We will not allow any of the verification activity, which is now
under way,' Mr Yun Ho-jin, a North Korean envoy, said.
The statement came after the board of the International Atomic Energy Agency
adopted a resolution condemning North Korea for violating safeguards
agreements by refusing inspectors access to sites suspected of involvement
in the secret production of nuclear weapons.
The board also suspended technical aid. China abstained on the vote. Though
limited in scope, the cut off in aid amounts to the first formal sanctions
against North Korea.
An intensive week of diplomatic shuttling by foreign ministers and officials
has so far failed to forge a common position on measures to be taken to
punish Pyongyang for its refusal to open its facilities to inspection.
China has refused to play ball, while Russia and to a lesser extent Japan
have been reluctant to give strong backing for a UN resolution.
In Istanbul Mr Warren Christopher ,the US secretary of State held talks on
North Korea with Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev on the fringes of a
Nato meeting with former communist adversaries, but had yet to reach
complete accord with Russia which first wanted an international conference
held on the issue. Mr Christopher however said he expected the US 'to be
putting forward a (sanctions) resolution within a few days' at the UN.
China has so far resolutely opposed sanctions. Yesterday President Jiang
Zemin said: 'Sanctions could have serious consequences, and China is against
such sanctions.'
Diplomatic efforts will continue today as Mr Koji Kakizawa, Japan's foreign
minister, goes to Seoul for meetings with President Kim Young-sam and
foreign minister Han Sung-joo. On Sunday, Mr Kakizawa will meet Qian Qichen,
China's foreign minister, to urge renewed efforts by Beijing to get the
North to permit inspections.
Mr Kakizawa will relay to China's leaders the hardening resolve of the
international community and urge them not to block a possible UN Security
Council resolution. Japan will co-operate with UN sanctions, but believes
efforts to seek a diplomatic solution should be continued to the last
minute.
Yesterday, Mr Kakizawa met Mr Peter Tarnoff, US undersecretary of state for
political affairs, and stressed China's role in a peaceful solution.
Hang-ups and hesitation, page 9
</TEXT>
<XX>
