<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Domestic problems mar Clinton's return
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Images of war cemeteries, military bands and proud old veterans have
surrounded President Bill Clinton for the last week, but they have done
little to change the landscape that awaited him on his return from Europe to
Washington.
The problems of Haiti, North Korea and Bosnia festered still, while on the
domestic front neither opinion polls nor election results offered the
president much comfort.
In a Gallup poll conducted for CNN and USA Today, only 49 per cent of those
questioned found Mr Clinton honest and trustworthy, although 78 per cent
thought him 'a nice guy.'
Meanwhile, candidates from Mr Clinton's own Democratic party continued to
distance themselves from him, and even the Democratic National Committee's
political director acknowledged that 'there are clearly some areas of the
country where it's not going to benefit a candidate to associate himself
with Bill Clinton' - a remark swiftly repudiated by the White House.
By general consensus, Mr Clinton struck just the right tone in his various
D-Day commemoration speeches, successfully soothing the niggling feeling
that his seat at these ceremonies would have been more appropriately filled
by former President George Bush, himself a second world war veteran.
However, his visit to Oxford, to the despair of some of his political
advisers, then presented a target few American journalists could resist.
'The student who came here avoiding military service and protesting a war
returned as president praising military service and avoiding the
protesters,' quipped Mr Brit Hume, correspondent of the ABC television
network.
The net effect on Mr Clinton's position is probably neutral as he approaches
three crucial weeks before the July 4 congressional recess.
Next week, the president is expected to unveil his proposals for 'ending
welfare as we know it,' a plan built around limiting benefits from the Aid
to Families with Dependent Children programme, the cornerstone of the US
social safety net, to two years.
But the ambitious reform programme, despite considerable support from both
parties in Congress, is probably stalled until next year, at the earliest,
as it must take second place on the legislative agenda to health care reform
Health care reform is making only slow progress, and Mr Clinton faces a
decision on how soon to involve himself in the struggle. Until now, the
White House has left the Congress to fight over the details, but the
president's own weight will be needed to push reform through.
The battle of health care has not been made any easier by the indictment of
Congressman Dan Rostenkowski, formerly chairman of the ways and means
committee, on charges of fraud and embezzlement.
Mr Rostenkowski was due to be arraigned in court yesterday, and was expected
to plead not guilty.
Mr Clinton's own legal travails, meanwhile, have not gone away during his
trip to Europe. In the next few weeks he will have to respond to the charges
of sexual harassment filed against him by a former Arkansas state employee.
Congressional hearings on his investment in the Whitewater property venture
are also expected to begin next month, although the Republicans and the
Democrats continue to wrangle about their scope.
</TEXT>
