<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Poll success for Irish Greens: Early estimates of European
Parliament voting Austria referendum tomorrow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE and RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Greens achieved a breakthrough in Ireland, while anti-EU parties gained
ground in Denmark, according to initial projections yesterday of the results
of Thursday's European Parliament voting.
Final results from the elections in Britain, the Netherlands, Ireland and
Denmark will not be known until tomorrow after the rest of the 12-nation EU
has voted for the Strasbourg-based parliament.
In the Netherlands, the main feature of Thursday's poll was a slump in voter
turnout to an all-time low of 35 per cent, down sharply from 47 per cent
five years ago.
However, the Christian Democrats of outgoing Dutch prime minister Ruud
Lubbers took heart from unofficial exit polls showing they emerged as the
strongest party in the election.
If confirmed, this would mean they would regain the position they lost to
Labour in national elections in May.
Exit polls showed that the Christian Democrats won 10 seats and Labour
eight. This would equal both parties' current representation, but mean a
relative decline, as the number of Dutch seats has been increased by six to
31.
Dutch political analysts said the low turnout benefited the Christian
Democrats and worked against Labour.
In Ireland, an unofficial count pointed to the Greens winning at least one,
and possibly two, of the 15 Irish seats.
Overturning poll predictions that the Greens would be weak outsiders, Ms Pat
McKenna, the party's candidate in the four-seat Dublin constituency, topped
the poll, according to figures collected by the main parties at the counting
station.
The two coalition parties, Fianna Fail and Labour, both suffered a drop in
first preference votes, although Fianna Fail looks set to achieve its target
of winning seven seats.
In Denmark, two anti-EU groups with no representation in Denmark's own
parliament, the People's Anti-EU Movement and the June Movement, looked set
to get five of the country's 16 Strasbourg seats, according to exit polls.
</TEXT>
