FT  11 JUN 94 / Groupe Schneider plans to call in outside auditor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Groupe Schneider is to call in an outside auditor to examine its tangled
relationship with Belgian and offshore subsidiaries, with a view to clearing
its president of fraud and swindling charges, the company said yesterday.
Attending his first board meeting since his release on bail from a Brussels
prison on Tuesday, Mr Didier Pineau-Valencienne got the board's 'unanimous
support and total confidence' that 'he had always acted in the interests of
all shareholders', a company statement said.
In an interview with Le Monde newspaper yesterday, Mr Pineau-Valencienne
said that with the board renewing its confidence in him, he was resuming his
functions as president and would be able to tell shareholders at next
Thursday's annual general meeting that the group was in good shape.
Expounding at length in the interview on his innocence of the charges
levelled at him by the Belgian judge, Mr Jean-Claude Van Espen, Mr
Pineau-Valencienne claimed that Schneider 'has never received, directly or
indirectly, any money from offshore subsidaries, other than through the
Belgian companies of Cofibel and Cofimines'.
Minority shareholders in those two companies had complained that Schneider
had cut them out of dividends due from Swiss and Panamian subsidaries, a
charge central to the Belgian investigation.
For the first time, Mr Pineau-Valencienne spoke publicly of the complicated
arrangements that the Belgian part of Schneider had put in place to manage
Zairean mining interests, involving a Swiss trust managing the Panamian
companies of Mitraco and Tramico. But he said their net worth was virtually
nil by this year, when they were apparently sold for a symbolic one franc.
He admitted that Scheider had made a mistake in investing in a company
called PB Finance, whose activities are the object of a separate
investigation by Judge Van Espen. But this investment had been made by the
late Mr Jean Verdoot, to whom Mr Pineau-Valencienne said he had left the
running of Schneider's Belgian interests after 1985.
The Schneider president protested at the way he had been initially
questioned almost continuously from 10am on May 26 until 5am the following
day, only then to be told that he was to be held in prison. This, he said,
was 'neither necessary or justified'.
