<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Yeltsin decree lifts curbs on foreign banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOLTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Boris Yeltsin, in a further push for economic reform, announced
yesterday that he had signed a long-awaited decree lifting severe
operational restrictions on western banks.
Accompanied by other measures such as the introduction of long-term housing
mortgages, the banking decree was a pre-condition for European union
ministers to endorse at a meeting in Luxembourg on Monday a partnership and
co-operation treaty with Russia.
Mr Yeltsin said the decree, which lists only those restrictions slapped
retroactively on half a dozen western banks which had previously received
full Russian banking licences, would 'spark criticism' from Russian banks
eager for protection from western competition. EU diplomats said
restrictions would be removed not just on EU banks but on US, Turkish and
Swiss banks which also suffered from the ban on banks taking deposits from
Russian customers.
'There must be gradual, cautious involvement of foreign banks in our
commercial and financial life,' Mr Yeltsin said.
He gave no details on the decree, which he said would also regulate local
banks and strengthen the central bank.
Last November Moscow froze new foreign bank entry to Russia until 1996,
imposed offshore status on licensed foreign banks and barred them from
dealing with Russian clients, in a decree aimed at wooing the country's
strong anti-western banking lobby.
However, the EU treaty to be signed in Corfu on June 20 still gives Russia
the right to close its fledgling financial markets to Europeans who may wish
to join it in future.
Mr Yeltsin for the first time also promised action to clean up Russia's
virtually unregulated financial markets. He said he planned a decree which
would combat fraudulent financial advertising and offer some protection to
millions of small shareholders created overnight by Russia's mass
privatisation campaign.
But he also badly let down a key reformer, Mr Anatoly Chubais, the deputy
prime minister for privatisation, by publicly ordering him not to try to
stop the Moscow mayor's 'special' privatisation plan which basically
short-circuits Mr Chubais's nationwide programme.
However, the Russian leader took a courageous stand under intense pressure
from the country's defence lobby for an increase in military expenditure
which would wreck the 1994 budget approved by the lower chamber of
parliament on Wednesday.
He told the military that the only way they would get extra finance would be
through non-budgetary sources - such as arms sales like a recent Dollars
550m (Pounds 367m) aircraft sale to Malaysia. He also told them they had to
do more to cut military procurement as well as Russia's 3m-strong army.
Finally, he said he had ordered the Interior Ministry and domestic
intelligence service to cleanse Russia of 'criminal filth', saying gangsters
were trying to grab hold of the economy and even to get into politics.
</TEXT>
