<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Stockholm doubts over Vienna vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and ANDREW GOWERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Carl Bildt, Sweden's prime minister, said the uphill task of persuading
Swedes to vote to join the EU this autumn would be even more difficult if
fellow-applicant Austria rejects membership in its referendum tomorrow.
But he admitted the severe doubts over the outcome of Sweden's November
plebiscite on the issue were unlikely to be dispelled by an Austrian Yes
vote, or by Finnish acceptance of membership in a similar referendum due in
October.
'We can be affected negatively if things go wrong (in Austria) - not to
mention the major catastrophe if things go wrong in both countries that will
hold a referendum before us. Whether there will be an effect in the other
direction - a positive effect (from a Yes vote) - is more doubtful,' he said
in an interview with the Financial Times.
Mr Bildt, who originally wanted to hold the Swedish referendum later this
month, expressed concern that the EU issue would be eclipsed by the campaign
for the general election on September 18, and the formation of a new
government in October. This would leave little time afterwards to overturn
opinion, at present running strongly against membership.
Mr Bildt, who leads a right-centre coalition, was sharply critical of the
leadership of the opposition Social Democratic party, the majority of whose
supporters are opposed to the EU, for not campaigning more actively for a
Yes vote: 'It is strange that the largest party in Sweden has not taken a
position on the largest issue in Sweden. . . I fear that we are past the
point at which it will be possible for the Social Democrats to get a
majority of their people on the Yes side.'
Mr Ingvar Carlsson, the Social Democratic leader, denied he was ducking the
EU question. But he said the general election should be fought on domestic
issues, leaving the EU campaign for afterwards. He said Mr Bildt's strident
advocacy of membership was alienating many voters: 'Every time he speaks, we
lose more votes to the No side.'
</TEXT>
