<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Lyonnaise des Eaux in protest at bribes allegations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jerome Monod, president of Lyonnaise des Eaux, yesterday threatened legal
action against Mr Thierry Jean-Pierre, a magistrate running in tomorrow's
European Parliament election, for alleging that Lyonnaise used bribes to win
water contracts and covered the cost by raising water charges to consumers,
David Buchan writes from Paris.
Mr Monod made his threat after anxious questioning about the 'political
corruption' allegations by some shareholders at Lyonnaise's annual general
meeting on Thursday and a slide on the same day in the share price of
Lyonnaise and also that of Generale des Eaux, the other big French utility
and communications group to be the target of Mr Jean-Pierre's recent
allegations in local and international newspapers. Generale des Eaux asked
the COB, which regulates the Paris Bourse, to put trading in its shares
under surveillance.
Mr Monod told his shareholders that he 'could not prevent the subsidiaries
(of Lyonnaise des Eauxz) from doing what is possible, permitted and
solicited with insistence' by political parties.
Lyonnaise argues that the differences in water charges across France reflect
differences in costs and that the tariffs are in any case under the control
of local authorities with which Lyonnaise has its contracts.
