<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Austrians likely to support entry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Austria's voters look set to vote narrowly in support of joining the
European Union in a referendum tomorrow.
The latest Gallup opinion poll on Thursday indicated that 57 per cent of
Austrians favoured membership, against only 28 per cent who would probably
cast 'No' ballots.
Earlier polls showed the two sides evenly balanced, with many voters
undecided. Austrians are known for making up their minds about voting only
at the last minute.
Investors have apparently accepted the message of the Gallup poll, buying
shares heavily on the Vienna Borse in the past three days. In the previous
six sessions, the ATX index of leading shares lost 5 per cent of its value
as fears of a rejection of the EU spread.
The campaign ended yesterday on the shrill tone that dominated debate in the
closing days. A story that Austrians would have to buy Spanish-made yoghurt
containing a harmful bacterial colouring agent was put about by right-wing
leader Mr Jorg Haider.
And the conservative Austrian People's party staged a rousing 60th birthday
party at Vienna's Hofburg Palace for Mr Alois Mock, the popular foreign
minister, who has fought passionately for the EU cause. Mr Mock has won
immense sympathy for his tireless campaigning in spite of a debilitating
nervous system disease.
The referendum result will be known early tomorrow evening.
</TEXT>
