<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / P&amp;G moves to avoid veto on takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Procter &amp; Gamble, the large US consumer goods manufacturer, is understood to
have made a last-minute offer to modify its controversial proposed takeover
of a leading German maker of feminine hygiene products, in an effort to win
Brussels' approval of the deal.
The offer is believed to have been made yesterday, soon after Mr Karel Van
Miert, the European competition commissioner, had won broad agreement from
senior advisers to his fellow commissioners that the takeover should be
blocked as anti-competitive.
Though the offer is thought to go some way to meet Mr Van Miert's main
objections to the deal, he is still expected to argue that it should be
prohibited in its original form when the full 17-member commission meets on
Wednesday. That would not prevent P&amp;G from filing a fresh application asking
Brussels to approve the takeover of Vereinigte Papierwerke Schickedanz, in
modified form.
Though the exact terms of P&amp;G's offer are not known, Brussels is understood
to have insisted that the deal could not go ahead unless the US company
agreed to divest several of Schickedanz's main German sanitary towel brands.
The shift in P&amp;G's tactics coincides with signs that Mr Van Miert plans to
enforce competition rules more rigorously in other areas. He is expected
soon to propose heavy fines on Europe's leading manufacturers of carton
board and cement for alleged price-fixing.
However, the commissioner is believed to be taking a more cautious line in
investigating the French government's plan to rescue Credit Lyonnais, the
troubled state-owned bank, by injecting FFr4.9bn (Pounds 570m) of capital
and writing off FFr40bn of bad debts.
Mr Van Miert is expected to set up a panel of eminent bankers to advise him
on the case - an unprecedented step in an EU competition inquiry.
If the P&amp;G takeover of Schickedanz were prohibited, it would be only the
second deal which the Commission has blocked since it was given increased
powers to vet large mergers more than two-and-a-half years ago.
The earlier veto, of the planned takeover of De Havilland, the Canadian
aircraft manufacturer, by Aerospatiale of France and Alenia of Italy,
provoked a storm of protest in Paris and Rome.
Brussels competition authorities have objected that the P&amp;G deal would give
the US company more than half the German market for women's sanitary towels
and a dominant position in the EU overall. P&amp;G's leading competitors also
oppose the takeover.
However, P&amp;G disputes the Commission's market share figures. The company's
supporters, said to include German federal and state ministers, have argued
that jobs could be lost if the deal does not go ahead.
The Commission investigation into carton board covers all the main EU
producers and was launched in 1991, after the British Printing Industries
Federation complained of co-ordinated price rises across Europe.
The cement case is one of the most important cartel investigations on
Brussels' books and centres on alleged price-fixing involving 77 producers
and industry associations.
</TEXT>
