<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Grand Met chief awarded life peerage in honours list
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Allen Sheppard, the chairman of Grand Metropolitan, and Lord Owen, one
of the principal peace brokers in the former Yugoslavia, are among the most
prominent figures from industry and politics to receive awards in the
Queen's birthday honours list, announced today.
Sir Allen, who has transformed his organisation from a hotels and brewing
group into one of the leading food, wines and spirits companies in the
world, is one of only three life peers created in today's list.
He heads a group of city figures who are honoured, including Mr Brian
Pitman, the chief executive of Lloyds Bank, and Mr Robert Evans, the former
chairman of British Gas, both of whom are knighted.
Lord Owen, the former British foreign secretary, is made a Companion of
Honour after his efforts to bring peace to Bosnia. Among other political
figures to receive awards are Sir Christopher Prout, the leader of the
Conservatives in the European parliament, and Mr Richard Needham, the trade
minister, both of whom become privy councillors.
There are knighthoods for three Tory MPs: Mr Andrew Bowden, MP for Brighton
Kemptown, Mr Kenneth Carlisle, MP for Lincoln, and Mr John Gorst, MP for
Hendon North.
Among the leading public servants who are knighted are Mr Paul Condon, the
Metropolitan Police Commissioner, and Professor William Stewart, the
government's chief scientific adviser, who was one of the main drafters of
the government's recent white paper on science policy. There is a
knighthood, too, for Professor David Tweedie, the chairman of the
accountancy standards board, who has pushed through major changes in the
profession.
There will be particular interest in the knighthood for Mr Paul Newall, the
Lord Mayor of London. The government caused a minor storm in the City last
autumn by not knighting him when he was appointed to the post, as is
traditional.
Figures from the academic world are also well represented.
Professor Sir David Phillips, a leading biophysicist, is another of the life
peers created in the list. The third - after Sir Allen Sheppard - is Sir
Randolph Quirk, one of the world's leading English literature professors.
Professor Laurence Martin, director of the Royal Institute of International
Affairs, is knighted.
Sir Alec Guinness, the actor, becomes a Companion of Honour. Miss Diana
Rigg, the actress, becomes a dame.
In the world of sport, Mr Bobby Charlton, the former Manchester United and
England footballer, is knighted. Among cricketers, Mr Viv Richards, the
former West Indies captain, becomes an OBE.
Today's list marks the latest attempt by the prime minister to broaden the
range of people in public life who receive honours. Around a third of those
in today's 1,000-strong list are voluntary and charitable workers, and there
are around 300 women.
Sweep of awards embraces great variety, Page 6
