<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JUN 94 / Threat of train strike deepens as offer refused
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The threat of a 24-hour strike by railway signalmen next Wednesday deepened
last night after it emerged that their union negotiators had rejected a 5.7
per cent pay offer from Railtrack designed to resolve the conflict.
The RMT transport union said the company's proposal was 'not nearly enough'
to satisfy the grievances of the signalmen, who are demanding an 11 per cent
interim wage increase as a condition for entering into talks with Railtrack
over the restructuring of their pay system.
Last night Railtrack denied that it had made any offer to the union.
The RMT said it had spent three days of 'exhaustive negotiations' this week
to try to avert a strike. 'We have made ourselves available to settle the
dispute as quickly as possible,' the union added. 'We have just been told
that the Railtrack board cannot make their minds up on what to offer staff.
They are at sixes and sevens.'
Further talks between the two sides are expected on Monday, but the RMT
warned last night that this was leaving little time to resolve the
signalmen's grievances. Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, said
yesterday: 'The claim has been outstanding for seven years. 'If our members
are forced to take strike action on Wednesday the fault lies with
Railtrack.'
Railtrack said that the board had to be called in from all over Britain and
there was no possibility of convening a meeting before Monday.
