<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Second place equals victory for Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When the result of the Eastleigh by-election was read out this morning, the
cheer from Labour supporters was so big that it was easy to forget they had
only come second. The Liberal Democrats had taken the seat with a 20 per
cent swing from the Tories - significantly lower than the last two
by-elections, but a comfortable win nonetheless.
But for Labour, its credibility as an outlet for disillusioned Tory voters
in the south had been on the line. By achieving its own target - of coming a
strong second - it succeeded in showing that it could win votes in the south
and prevent itself from being squeezed by the Liberal Democrats.
The Liberal Democrats pointed to an eve-of-poll leaflet distributed by
Labour predicting that it would win Eastleigh by 6,000 votes. But no one,
least of all Labour's own officials, believed the contest was between the
two opposition parties. Both the Conservatives and Labour had privately
conceded victory to the Liberal Democrats long ago.
Labour, which has never fought so hard for a seat it had no hope of winning,
managed to push the Tories into third place. Miss Marilyn Birks, Labour
candidate, said last night she had succeeded in showing disillusioned Tories
in the south that Labour was a realistic alternative.
She said: 'This by-election has been a referendum on the Tory government and
the voters have given them a clear message that their policies have failed.'
Mr Tony Blair, favourite for the Labour leadership, had been vindicated in
showing that Labour had become sufficiently attractive to win votes in the
south of England. Labour had taken the risk in deciding not to 'relinquish'
its votes for Liberal Democrats - as it grandly did in Newbury - and the
gamble had paid off.
But Labour was helped by a turnout that was significantly lower than usual.
Only 58.9 per cent turned out, compared with 83 per cent in the last
election. Mr David Willets, the Conservative MP minding the Tory candidate,
Mr Steven Reid, said it was clear that many Tory voters had stayed at home
while the majority of disillusioned Conservatives had defected to the
Liberal Democrats. He said: 'The fight to take this seat back at the next
general election starts on Monday.'
Mr Willets consoled himself with the fact that those who abstained were
supporters of the government. 'They'll come out again at the next election,'
he said.
Mr David Chidgey, Liberal Democrat candidate, said Liberal Democrats knew
better than most that there were no prizes for coming second. He said he was
'delighted' with his majority of more than 9,000, which was significantly
larger than the Liberal Democrats had been expecting.
He added: 'This is a clear message to the prime minister - change your
policies or change your job.'
Liberal Democrats also pointed out that Labour had fought the campaign to
win and had lost. As one Liberal official said: 'You have to go back to 1962
to find a Labour gain in the south of England (when Dorset South was taken
by the official opposition).'
While the two opposition parties were pleased with their respective results,
the only obvious losers were the Conservatives.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
