<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / London results grim for Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The by-election results in the four Labour-held seats were less spectacular
than the crushing Conservative defeat in Eastleigh. But they still represent
very bad news for Mr John Major.
On the basis of the 1992 general election results, the Conservatives started
second in all four seats - Bradford South in West Yorkshire, and the three
east London seats of Barking, Dagenham and Newham North East.
By the end of counting early this morning, they had finished a humiliating
third in Bradford South and Barking, and a poor second in Dagenham and
Newham, where they were helped by the last-minute defection to Labour of
Liberal Democrat Mr Alec Kellaway.
Labour's vote rose strongly in all four seats - by 20 per cent in Dagenham,
17 per cent in Newham, 22 per cent in Barking and 8 per cent in Bradford.
The Conservatives were down 26 per cent, 7 per cent, 21 per cent and 21 per
cent respectively.
Sir Norman Fowler, Tory party chairman, admitted that the results were 'very
disappointing', but claimed that the impact of the defeat would be muted by
an 'amazingly low' turnout in all four constituencies. 'By any analysis, a
lot of people are simply staying away and not voting,' he said on BBC
television. 'That gives us the opportunity to recover and regain our
support.'
Nevertheless, the polling is deeply depressing for the Conservatives, who
had pinned their hopes of remaining a credible force in Labour seats on
coming second in all four seats. Labour hailed the results as a signal that
the government's popularity had fallen too far for the Tories to have much
hope of recovering ground in London before the next general election.
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow minister for London, said the east London results
were 'stunningly good' and 'very disturbing for the government'. Mr Nick
Raynsford, Labour campaign organiser for London, said the results reinforced
Labour's standing as the biggest party in the capital.
The results were mixed for the Liberal Democrats, who finished second in
Bradford South with 24 per cent of the vote, up 10 per cent on the general
election; and in Barking, with 12 per cent, down from 14.5 per cent.
The poor result in Newham - where the party polled just 821 votes - was
expected because of the embarrassment and confusion caused by the defection
of Mr Kellaway. But Liberal Democrat strategists will be disappointed not to
have done better in Dagenham, where their share of the vote fell by 3
percentage points to 8.4 per cent.
The feared revival of the extreme right in London did not materialise. The
British National Party came fourth in Dagenham, but won only 1,511 votes in
spite of pouring in resources for the campaign. The National Front won only
551 votes in Barking.
Ms Judith Church, the victor in Dagenham, said the extreme right had been
'firmly' rejected. 'This is a wonderful defeat for them and a wonderful
victory for us,' she said.
