<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Yemen ceasefire dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ADEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Yemen's rival armies made a fresh ceasefire attempt yesterday but southern
leaders accused northern forces of breaking their own self-declared truce
within hours of its taking effect, Reuter reports from Aden. After a day of
northern artillery fire on the southern stronghold of Aden, Sanaa television
reported northern President Ali Abdullah Saleh had ordered his forces to
observe a ceasefire from 6 pm yesterday. Southern Yemen, which broke away
from a four-year union with the north on May 21, agreed to the truce but
later said Mr Saleh's troops had launched a surprise attack including heavy
artillery bombardments of its forces.
