<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Danes show support for anti-Europeans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign and Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Danish anti-European parties attracted some of the strongest support in
polling among the four European Union countries where elections were held
yesterday for an expanded European parliament.
However, according to one poll, the strongly pro-union Liberal party, led by
Mr Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, the former foreign minister, stood to add one seat
to win four of Denmark's 16 seats.
Exit polls indicated that Denmark's two anti-European parties, which are not
represented in the country's national parliament, increased their share of
the vote to about 25 per cent from 18.9 per cent at the last election in
1989. But they were not expected to add to their four seats in the last
parliament.
The Social Democratic party, which dominates the present government
coalition, was expected to lose one of its four seats. Its share of the vote
appeared to have fallen to about 15 per cent from 23.3 per cent. Mr Poul
Nyrup Rasmussen, the prime minister, said it was 'a clearly disappointing
result'.
The pro-union Centre Democratic party also appeared likely to have lost both
its seats, with its share of the vote falling from 7.9 per cent to about 1
per cent.
The polls indicated a turnout of 52 per cent in Denmark, up from 46.2 per
cent. But turnout appeared to have fallen in the UK and the Netherlands
while in Ireland, the fourth country where voting took place, it was
estimated at between 40 per cent and 50 per cent of the 2.6m voters. This
compared with 48 per cent in 1989.
Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, the Belgian prime minister who is a possible successor
to Mr Jacques Delors as European Commission president, said he was
distressed by the low turnout.
The elections appeared to have strengthened the position of the Dutch
Christian Democrat party, which emerged as the largest party in the
Netherlands, reclaiming the position it lost in national elections last
month. Preliminary forecasts reported by Dutch television last night showed
that the Christian Democrats stood to win 11 seats in the European
parliament, three seats ahead of Labour, which is now the largest party in
the national parliament. For the Christian Democrats, the results would mean
a gain of one seat in the European parliament, with Labour unchanged.
Elections for the expanded 567-seat parliament will take place in the other
eight EU countries on Sunday.
</TEXT>
