<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / Tories suffer crushing defeat: Major faces massive Euro-poll
losses as Lib Dems triumph in Eastleigh
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, KEVIN BROWN and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's government was facing a mid-term electoral catastrophe early
this morning after crashing to a humiliating third-place defeat at the hands
of the Liberal Democrats in the Eastleigh by-election.
The loss of the once-safe seat and a massive anti-government swing in four
other by-elections raised the prospect of a performance in the European
elections worse than even the Conservatives' most dire expectations.
Initial projections raised the question whether the Tory representation in
the Strasbourg assembly would fall from the present 32 seats to just a
handful, an outcome which would re-ignite the threat to Mr Major's
leadership. Labour and the Liberal Democrats, which treated the elections as
a referendum on the prime minister's record, were both anticipating
spectactular gains.
As Sir Norman Fowler, the Tory party chairman, sought to dismiss suggestions
that Mr Major's premiership will be plunged into fresh crisis, Mr Paddy
Ashdown's Liberal Democrats overturned a Tory majority in Eastleigh of more
than 17,000 at the 1992 general election.
Completing a hat-trick of by-election victories over the past year, Mr David
Chidgey, the Liberal Democrat candidate secured a majority of 9,239 in the
poll caused by the death earlier this year of Mr Stephen Milligan. The swing
against the Conservatives was 21.5 per cent.
Mr Stephen Reid, the Conservative candidate, was forced into a humiliating
third place in a previously safe Tory seat after a vigorous campaign by
Labour's Mrs Marilyn Birks.
A massive protest vote against the government across the country was
underlined by a similar collapse in the Conservative vote in four other
by-elections in which Labour held on to previously safe seats.
In Bradford South and Barking, a massive 21 per cent anti-government swing
forced the Conservatives into third place behind the Liberal Democrats.
Labour won comfortably also in Newham North East and Dagenham. But in all
four seats there were extremely low turnouts.
Mr David Butler, a leading psephologist and fellow of Nuffield College
Oxford, said the by-election results were 'as devastating as they could be'.
The Conservative vote was on average 23 per cent down on the 1992 general
election.
If replicated in the European elections when the results are announced on
Sunday evening, the Eastleigh swing from the Conservatives to the Liberal
Democrats was enough for them to win all the Strasbourg seats where they are
the main challenger to the Conservatives. The swing from the Conservatives
to Labour in the four other by-elections would guarantee a Labour win in
every Conservative euro-seat where they are the main challenger.
A low turnout in the European poll suggested that core Conservative voters
had ignored last minute pleas from the prime minister to support his
opposition to a centralised federal Europe. Early indications were that less
than 40 per cent of the electorate had turned out. Sir Norman acknowledged
early this morning that the government was heading for a serious defeat but
insisted that Mr Major's position was secure.
The prime minister, who took a high-profile personal role in the campaign,
has repeatedly stressed he will fight any challenge to his leadership. But
the return to Westminster early next week of Tory MPs is certain to fuel
speculation about a challenge to the prime minister in the autumn.
Exit surveys indicated that Conservative support in some areas had
collapsed. A straw poll in Norfolk by the Eastern Daily Press suggested a 19
percentage points swing from the Tories to Labour.
A straw poll in four West of England seats for Westcountry Television
suggested a swing of about 18 points from the Conservatives to the two
opposition parties. About two-thirds of the extra votes were going to the
Liberal Democrats. However, election analysts warned that the polls were not
based on scientific samples.
The Conservatives had hoped that a late swing to the party could allow it to
hold up to 20 seats. However the latest opinion poll, by Mori for The Times,
indicated that the party could be left with as few as four seats. The poll
gave the Conservatives 23 per cent of the vote, compared with 51 per cent
for Labour, and 20 per cent for the Liberal Democrats.
Tory bastion looking vulnerable, Page 12
Joe Rogaly, Page 18
