<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / PepsiCo shares drop9% over price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in PepsiCo, US maker of the soft drink Pepsi-Cola, lost 9 per cent of
their value by the close of trade yesterday, after the company shocked Wall
Street with news that a cola price war had broken out in its domestic
market.
PepsiCo fell Dollars 3 1/4 to close at Dollars 31 1/2 while Coca-Cola
dropped Dollars  7/8 to finish at Dollars 40 3/4 .
PepsiCo warned that second-quarter profits would be flat because of the
inroads being made into the US cola market by Cott, the fast-growing
Canadian maker of low-cost, store-branded foods and drinks.
Cott recently sparked a row in the UK by supplying J. Sainsbury, the
country's biggest retailer, with a store-branded cola that looks and tastes
similar to Coca-Cola but sells at roughly half the price. Coca-Cola accused
Sainsbury of trying to pass off Cott's product as 'the real thing'.
PepsiCo's announcement left investors worried because it called to mind last
year's 'Marlboro Friday', when Philip Morris, US manufacturer of Marlboro
cigarettes, slashed prices in response to cut-price competition.
The development also reinforced worries on Wall Street about the true worth
of brands at a time when value-conscious consumers seem inclined to switch
away from famous-name products if they feel they can get the same quality at
a lower price.
Cott is the largest supplier of store-branded soft drinks in North America.
The company has begun to spread outside North America to South Africa and
Australia, and signed an agreement with Cadbury Schweppes of the UK that
should allow it to distribute its products throughout Europe.
World stocks, Page 41
