<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US beverages hit by warning
from PepsiCo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices held fairly steady in quiet trading yesterday, but investors
in beverage stocks were rattled by a profits warning issued by PepsiCo,
writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 3.69 better at 3,753.14 and the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 drifted 0.80 higher to 457.86. The Nasdaq composite
dipped 0.91 to 728.88, although technology stocks stabilised after
Wednesday's sharp fall. NYSE volume remained moderate, totalling 253m
shares.
Before the opening, most market observers were expecting a tranquil trading
session. There was no important economic news scheduled for release and the
bond market was taking a breather ahead of today's report on May producer
prices.
A shred of news was forthcoming from the Labor Department, which said
initial claims for state unemployment benefit held steady last week. But the
development was brushed aside.
However, investors were unable to ignore an announcement by PepsiCo. The big
soft drinks group said its second-quarter earnings would show no improvement
over last year's result.
After a delayed opening, the stock tumbled Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 31 1/2 .
Adding to its distress, at least two securities houses, Smith Barney and
Bear Stearns, lowered their ratings on the issue.
PepsiCo's warning carried implications for the entire beverage industry,
since it linked its flat performance to slumping prices in the US soft
drinks business.
The trend was presumed to have affected Coca-Cola, too. Its share price was
marked down Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 40 3/4 on heavy volume of some 3.5m
shares. Payment of the company's dividend yesterday contributed to the extra
activity.
Cott, a leading private label soft drinks bottler, dropped Dollars 1 1/4 to
Dollars 18 1/8 , although analysts said its aggressiveness was behind the
pricing pressures within the industry.
Snapple, which specialises in iced tea drinks, receded Dollars 1 3/4 to
Dollars 25 1/4 . It was the second consecutive day in which the former
darling of the stock market suffered heavy losses. Ironically, the reason
for the markdown was stiffer competition from Lipton, a line marketed
jointly by PepsiCo and Unilever.
The damage triggered by PepsiCo's announcement also spilled over into the
fast-food business, where soft drink sales are a mainstay.
McDonald's retreated Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 60. Its weakness was the
biggest restraint on the Dow industrials, most of which were showing modest
gains.
On a brighter note, many technology stocks steadied after fears of a
slowdown in personal computer orders had triggered a sell-off in the
previous session.
However, the industry was facing another big hurdle, with the Semiconductor
Industry Association set to release its May 'book-to-bill' ratio just after
the close. The figure is regarded as a reliable indicator of the future
performance of computer companies.
Before its release, Texas Instruments fell Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 74 7/8
and Applied Materials lost Dollars 2 to Dollars 38 3/8 .
With computer sales expected to flag, office-supply retailers were feeling
the pinch. Office Depot weakened Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 34 3/8 and Staples
Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 27 7/8 .
Canada
A further fall for the Toronto market was followed by a late-session rally
that left the TSE 300 composite index just 4.5 off on the day at 4,196.8.
The index was down 25 points at midday.
Declines led rises by 456 to 306. Volume was light at 43.5m shares. Ten of
the 14 sub-indices closed lower, led by utilities, down 1.2 per cent. The
mining group had the day's biggest rise, up 1.4 per cent.
Cineplex Odeon rose 15 cents to CDollars 4.70. The company said at its
annual meeting that it is in a 'prime position' for a possible merger or
major acquisition, but added that a deal is not imminent.
Brazil
Shares in Sao Paulo closed 3.8 per cent stronger after moderate trade,
prices having rebounded from an early profit-taking wave tied to bearish
news on the presidential race. The Bovespa index added 1,106 at 29,324.
Turnover came to Cr561.2bn (Dollars 269.5m).
Brokers said prices rallied in late trade on lingering optimism ahead of the
introduction of the new currency, the real, on July 1.
The market declined at the opening following publication of an opinion poll
by Ibope private research institute which showed that left-wing presidential
candidate Mr Luiz Inacio 'Lula' da Silva was maintaining a strong lead over
rivals with 39 per cent of the poll. Former economy minister Mr Fernando
Henrique Cardoso had 17 per cent.
</TEXT>
